INSERT INTO `stories` (`id`, `Story_Number`, `Name_of_ppt`, `Contact_details`, `Date_of_story`, `Story_Format`, `Migration_Category`, `Migration_Sub-Category`, `Migration_Sub-Category1`, `Migration_Sub-Category2`, `Country`, `Exhibition`, `Disc_Type`, `Other_Interactive_Format`, `Story`, `Keywords`, `AI_Keywords`, `Link_to_transcript_file`, `Link_to_raw_data_audio_video_image`, `Completed_by`, `Notes`, `reviewed`, `votes`) VALUES
(1, '1', 'Juan Delgado', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] When I arrived in London, the first week I walked down the Southbank and I remember it was seven o’clock in the early evening and suddenly all these street lamps went on.\n \n[00:00:16] And It was really for me an amazing feeling that the city was welcoming. I feel I was part of this city from the very moment I arrived. I never felt alienated. I never felt like I was a foreigner. I felt like the city was embracing me.\n \n[00:00:36] My first room I slept on a sofa for eight months and eventually I found my own place that was a room with a family from India.\n \n[00:00:48] I remember that for the first time I was posed in a very intimate environment, with people from another culture.\n \n[00:00:58] What I really loved when I arrived in London was the huge amount of diversity of people, that were completely unexpected.\n \n[00:01:12] Being in London really for me represents a wonderful opportunity of learning from people who are different to me, having different customs and cultures. I love that.', 'Assimilation;Community;Culture;India;Pride', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1gqrpv3qjaPPQLfNdn4ziBaOyEEXWjbTNnsLtT8BEsvg/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/18XYiE7pr2d6iDEWXg0rushw1WK_drKND/view?usp=sharing', 'Nanda', NULL, 0, 0),
(2, '2', 'Sonia', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Colombia', 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] I live at a Victorian house in Croydon. Five rooms, two floors and the garden. The garden was the same size as the house. So, you can imagine the house was huge.\n \n[00:00:11] The owner was an old man. He was the same age as my dad but the opposite in character. The contrast was impressive. My father was very abusive, and he was a gambler. Sometimes we lost but when he won a play in cards or chess he could keep us going for two years.\n \n[00:00:30] The old man welcomed my girlfriend and I, as if we were his daughters. When we arrived at that house, we lived in one room. And all the others were full of beds, mattresses, washing machines, typewriters, etc.\n \n[00:00:45] When we made our partnerships, he was with us and carried the rings and he took good care of us. We didn’t pay rent for the time we were there.\n \n[00:00:56] When I broke up with my partner, he took my side. I took care of this man when he was dying of cancer for two years. When he died, I was there in the house holding his hands. I let go of something with that last breath. And I spoke to him as if he was my dad, in Spanish.\n \n[00:01:18] So, my memory of that house were very healing and very calm. Very different from Colombia. In that house in Croydon, I feel like home.', 'Celebration;Community;Colombia;Family;Language;Pride', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1-q1y2YWOAKM9rudwTQJrC-MebnGCiYTTX8ZYgSrR03Q/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/drive/u/1/folders/1x5ReGSPDlRBerDNXCgiyMx5I_ZOJ74_M', 'Nanda', NULL, 0, 0),
(3, '3', 'Antonia', NULL, '1960s', 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Nigeria', 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] I came here in 1966 from Nigeria at the age of 22 and I was living in a hostel because my parents wanted somewhere that is secure and there, I was very homesick.\n \n[00:00:16] Fortunately, I was sharing a room with a young violinist. Not much communication at first, but I keep on crying.\n \n[00:00:26] Wow, you cut off everything, you have college in the morning, you have breakfast, go to college and in the evening, you have evening meal and that is it. And I cried but I see this young lady just playing her violin and I said to myself where do you come from. And she told me where I came from. So, if she is just getting on, what is for me not doing the same thing.\n \n[00:00:57] I even got a picture of her and she was studying - don\'t know where, but she is always forever playing her violin and that even did not disturb me because it became some sort of therapy.\n \n[00:01:13] And even truly I loved someone like Tchaikovsky because it reminds me of this young lady. I learned from this person. I was swallowing in self-pity but eventually I got out of it.', 'Alienation;Education;Music;Nigeria;Wellbeing', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/12Rezb9zceURBZ5Q26B7B8fcx16FRxIC90aVXngBgYco/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/drive/u/1/folders/1x5ReGSPDlRBerDNXCgiyMx5I_ZOJ74_M', 'Nanda', NULL, 0, 0),
(4, '4', 'Herman Ousely', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] My first home was sharing a room, a bedroom, we were in one room. Within a multipole occupied house in Peckham, South London. In which I was sharing a bed with my mum at the time.\n \n[00:00:18]\nWe didn’t have to share a communal kitchen, we had to share a communal bathroom for the other four or five families living in the house and that was it. And within a space of months, we would have regularly milk bottles coming through the windows. They were bordered up for quite some time.\n \n[00:00:41]\nSo, it was a bit of harrowing experience, but the living conditions were very much cramped. In a sense you almost felt grateful that you were in a situation even though a milk bottle might be coming through the window, that you have a refuge.\n \n[00:01:00]\nAnd so, from my point of view I wasn’t looking for comfort. I was satisfied with being undercover and knowing there was a place to rest even though it wasn’t the best.\n \n[00:01:14]\nThat was the beginning, and it did improve as we went along, an improvement continued.', 'Alienation;Assimilation;Family', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1fgcSiY-nmekotNL1dT7bxjGwn-k4Z2mbBAAeZyrk9MQ/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/drive/u/1/folders/1x5ReGSPDlRBerDNXCgiyMx5I_ZOJ74_M', 'Nanda', NULL, 0, 0),
(5, '5', 'Andrey Sidelnikov', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Refugee/Asylum', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] After arriving to Gatwick, I stayed in the airport and I had a visa, a tourist visa but I asked for asylum at the airport.\n[00:00:12] For the first two weeks, I lived in a hotel and then I just was walking around and sitting in the centre I saw Russian newspaper, Angliya. [00:00:23] I just went looking for one room, saw it and said to the owner, “I’ll take it”. Couple bedroom, wardrobe, some table chair and internet [laughs]. It was the most important thing at the time and in my life too.', 'Pride;Russia;War', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/124EL8rrUcvrumT6fPaIxQ4nc877ci6tlJ4ox5Isb-Gc/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/drive/u/1/folders/1x5ReGSPDlRBerDNXCgiyMx5I_ZOJ74_M', 'Nanda', NULL, 0, 0),
(6, '6', 'Malgosia', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Economic', NULL, NULL, 'Poland', 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] I left my country because I wanted to have a better and more supportive life. And I found myself completely on my own, exhilarating, amazing, exciting but also terribly lonely because there was no one to go to.\n[00:00:19]\nAt least we have these Virgin stores with all of their CD’s. I bought all the music I always wanted to listen to. [00:00:27]\n[Music plays: The Miseducation of Lauryn Hill by Lauryn Hill]\n[00:00:41]\nThat made me feel so good, and I bought all the food I always dreamt of having. All the unusual fruit, the exotic things one couldn’t find in a small village in Poland. So that is what made me feel like at home strangely enough. I don’t feel anywhere at home unless it’s my own house. [00:01:03]\nSo, I suppose I created here my own house. I was told I can’t paint, I shouldn’t paint, I shouldn’t do it, it’s terrible I’m a woman I should be this and that. And I did it, that gives a meaning to my life and making my home. Sewing and cooking and painting the walls and decorating my home and making it cosy and special and lighting the candles, that makes me really well.', 'Alienation;Assimilation;Food;Music;Poland;Pride;Wellbeing', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1JosQVMbzgZnrmw9M6OQEhvGFnrPi56Pf/edit?rtpof=true', 'https://drive.google.com/drive/u/1/folders/1x5ReGSPDlRBerDNXCgiyMx5I_ZOJ74_M', 'Nanda', NULL, 0, 0),
(7, '7', 'Alvin Chung', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Child Migration', 'Education', NULL, NULL, 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] We lived in Tooting Bec and then my parents decided, they were offered a council space in a place called Carshalton which is just outside of Tooting, I would say a predominantly white area.\n[00:00:15] My first school was a school called Tweeddale School and out of around about 500 children I was the only black child\n[00:00:23] So from about day one when I went to school I kind of got racism. People calling me names and it was a few people who was curious because they had never seen a black person before or been that close to one. [00:00:35] I was chased a lot, I didn’t actually go complain to the teachers, I just had to deal it myself. People was calling me names, “black jag, wog, n****r, darkie” and so for the first few months I fought people. Then when I got to my sort of halfway of my second year of junior school, I said to myself I don’t think I’m going to be at cope with this when I get to senior school in the next six months because in the next four or five years I’m going to be there and I have to be like, I can’t be fighting everybody all the time\n[00:01:11] So basically what I decided to do, I decided to not be offended by it at all, not get riled up, not get upset, don’t let these people upset me anymore. So, when they did come up to me and started to call me “wog n****r” and just said to them well look if that means I’m a black person then that’s exactly what I am. And I think that diffuses the whole situation. [00:01:35] And eventually, it did die down. They stopped calling me those sorts of names because there wasn’t any point because it did not make a difference to me whatsoever… Even though there was racism in my school – in both my schools, I had my friends – I had white friends because there was nobody else.', 'Alienation;Education;Friends;Race;Racism', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/15x9yr5lC2WAcrpv7WqMjtv63cbG0VrAW/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/drive/u/1/folders/1OrqUGGBtBLVlPbJm755H7KUWJOMGpKQU', 'Nanda', NULL, 0, 0),
(8, '8', 'Bushra Nasir', NULL, '1960s', 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Child Migration', 'Education', NULL, 'Pakistan', 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] I arrived on the first of November 1960 with my mother and the four siblings, we separated from my father for four years, so it was really lovely to see him after four years. A couple weeks later my father organised for us obviously to start school. [00:00:15] We went to Churchmead School but we obviously we didn’t speak any English at all, so my father just tried very hard just to teach us two words, “yes” and “no” and I remember on the first day at break time a really lovely girl just pulled out a bag of sweets and she put it out to me and said, “do you want sweets?” and I said “no” and she put the sweets back and I realised that was the wrong word to have used.\n[00:00:46] She learned very very quickly and became head teacher of Plashet School in Newham in 1 and it was very interesting for me because I been a deputy of that same school for two and a half years and I was particularly attracted to be the head of Plashet because ninety percent of the students were from ethnic minorities. Some were first generation, some were new arrivals, some were second generations and I felt for me being a very positive role model was very key to this job. [00:01:20] That I was influencing the life of- when I left it was fourteen hundred students in my school and if you think of parents, three thousand parents really for those girls and so and so, in the school and the whole community was going to be influenced by my actions. So purposely I kept my dress code which I’m very proud of, I always tried to wear a smart jacket.\n[00:01:44] One of the things I purposely made a decision to do which was to always wear a shalwar kameez. I wanted to show my identity very very clearly, for them to value their background, not to feel as if it’s going to be brushed under the carpet and because of my experiences I had, I was always really keen that nothing prevented the girls from accessing their education.', 'Community;Culture;Education;Ethnicity;Family;Food;Language;Pride', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Jd9V9-sh0-XTOgdw59d7rnE4rFY2J-G_/edit?rtpof=true', 'https://drive.google.com/drive/u/1/folders/1OrqUGGBtBLVlPbJm755H7KUWJOMGpKQU', 'Nanda', NULL, 0, 0),
(9, '9', 'Carolina Caicedo', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Child Migration', NULL, NULL, 'Colombia', 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] Hola me llamo Carolina Caicedo. Tengo triente tres anos naci en Cali, Colombia pero ahora vivo en Londres. [00:00:09] My name is Carolina Caicedo, I was born in Cali, Colombia and moved to London with my parents and my sister when I was six years old. I ended up at this school in Battersea called Sacred Heart and upon reflection now, I am always amazed at how welcomed I was at that school. I didn’t speak any English and I just remembered I instantly had; I mean I wish I can remember their names; I just instantly had these two girls sort of instantly take me in and look after me even though I couldn’t speak English, so I have no idea of what they thought of me or how we communicated but I never ever had the feeling of feeling alienated or scared I suppose. [00:00:58] The school was just really diverse, there were just kids from all over the world. I wasn’t the only Latino there was this boy called Brian and a boy called Sergio and they were both Colombian, there was a guy called Bruno who I think was Portuguese we sort of had extra English classes with this incredible Australian teacher and I just loved it and I loved the school and I just felt it was a place that really celebrated difference.\n[00:01:25] I must have been like what six, seven or something? And I choreographed this piece with the other two Colombian boys, so Brian and Sergio to a cumbia and you know my teacher let me do that and I was just so proud.\n[00:01:42] My parents didn’t let us have school dinners at primary school because they weren’t very nice so we would have packed lunch. My mom will cook us a meal, it might be chicken, rice but it was different from what everyone else was having which was like crisps, sandwiches, peanut butter and jam sandwiches on white bread. People would sort of look at our packed lunch and be like “ahh what is that”, “what are you having?” and all you wanted in the world was to have what everyone else had and not your sort of ‘smelly’ and ‘different’ food. [Laughs]\n[00:02:17] So I left that primary school to go to secondary school and my sister and I got an assisted place to go to a private school in Streatham and it was a totally different experience, the majority of the school was white girls and the message there was very clear. To succeed was to assimilate and I suppose the shock for me was a class one, you know going to a private school, a very middle class setting, kind of very quickly having to learn English middle-class norms.\n[00:02:52] It’s interesting reflecting back to these primary school days where I choreographed something, and I used to love singing and I would stand up in front of the class and sing. There’s a sense of like just creativity and I now look at that secondary school and I feel like all of that was kind of killed there and too much of my energy went to assimilating and one’s own difference wasn’t celebrated and then you become this sort of shy more introverted person I guess where you are watching and you’re learning and observing and that’s kind of the role you sort of have to learn to take on in order to kind of succeed.', 'Assimilation;Class;Colombia;Culture;Education;Food;Friends;Language;Music;Portugal;Pride', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1nbMLtwLNSZD5Sq2caMAvh2L2ni6u6bjZ/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/drive/u/1/folders/1OrqUGGBtBLVlPbJm755H7KUWJOMGpKQU', 'Nanda', NULL, 0, 0),
(10, '10', 'Cathy Robinson', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Ireland', 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] We were all white, but I was treated very differently, and I remember there was this girl and I never forget, she used to tell lies on me, she said I pushed this girl over. Christine Beamish would say “she did push you, didn’t she?!”. And the girl went “yeah” just cos I think she was bit frightened of Christine and then she told the teacher. [00:00:22] And Christine Beamish didn’t like me because I was Irish. I had an Irish accent, but I didn’t know that then and I thought “I wonder why she told a lie on me”. I didn’t say “what did you sat that for?” because I was kind of shy and out of place completely. [00:00:40] There was kids with Irish names, but they weren’t Irish they were like the rest of the class, they were English. I remember feeling very not with anybody else, I felt very much on my own. I used to get in trouble with my dad for saying I ‘-ave’ that instead of have and he used to say “where are your h’s? have you dropped them under the table?” and about me speaking properly.\n[00:01:08] But I realised, I was trying to speak like everybody else so that I wouldn’t be so obvious.', 'Alienation;Assimilation;Culture;Education;Ethnicity;Family;Ireland;Language;Race', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1NdTdzotAp3em2V6kefBIFY9pVDEZUSH8/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/drive/u/1/folders/1OrqUGGBtBLVlPbJm755H7KUWJOMGpKQU', 'Nanda', NULL, 0, 0),
(11, '11', 'Doreen Bourne', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Pakistan', 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] She been in the country for six weeks, didn’t know anybody, she was brought into me and presented to me without anybody with her of course, no language, I couldn’t converse with her. And she just stood in the middle of my classroom and cried and cried and cried. [00:00:20] She wouldn’t sit down and of course the other children were all concerned about her so I put her a chair so she could sit down if she wanted to and carry on doing interesting things and she did come round.\n[00:00:33] She was a delightful little girl, and she sucked all the learning and the language with no trouble at all. I’ve always been amazed at how they can do that and at the end of the year she stood at the hall in front of all the classes because there were about twenty classes in our primary school.\n[00:00:45] She held up a picture that she drawn and talked about it to the people there and I cried. (Laughs) but that didn’t happen very often mostly they came in from nursery, she went home as usual, and I went into school on Monday as usual. [00:01:09] I was met with a group of children saying, “Mrs.Bourne, Mrs. Bourne, Saeeda is dead, Saeeda is dead”. They were all shouting, and I said “what?”. I mean it was Monday morning, I hardly woken up and it just been the classroom to tell me. I had come down and realised what had happened and I was shaking by then.\n[00:01:27] So he took over the class and said upstairs, go get yourself a coffee, which I did. They had photos taken the week before and Saeeda’s mum didn’t want hers or rather her father didn’t want her photo, but I still got it and I got a model that she made for her mum and dad. So, I pumped up courage, put a headscarf on, got trousers on anyway, I’ve never done anything like this before, nobody suggested it.\n[00:01:57] I went round to where they live cos, I knew the road. Knocked on the door and the men were all in the front room arranging the funeral, she got to be taken back to Pakistan. And I showed them the picture and they pointed to the back room. So, I went to the back room and they were all these ladies sitting round the room, crying and crying and wailing and they pointed at Saeeda’s mother and I thought well, what do I do?\n[00:02:26] So I went over to Saeeda’s mother, sat down in front of her, [00:02:31] Put my hands out\n[00:02:33] She grabbed hold of my hands and we cried and cried. I cried as well by that time I lost it you know. She clasps the photo, and she was hugging it to her chest, you know. Anyway, after all those women hadn’t been out, not seen one of the teachers. they were in purdah. [00:02:50] I didn’t know that I just crashed here, I don’t know these things, but the school was very pleased with me because I had actually reached a little gap there and I could go into that community which I found, I was quite pleased I was able to do that. If I would’ve have known, I’ll be nervous of going and checking if it was alright, but I just treated her just like any child in my class as you would.', 'Alienation;Community;Culture;Education;Family;Language;Pakistan;Pride;Religion;Third person;Wellbeing', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1YTgK88Mnlh_6zYlY2B1CxrcLbrHyPF7z/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/drive/u/1/folders/1OrqUGGBtBLVlPbJm755H7KUWJOMGpKQU', 'Nanda', NULL, 0, 0),
(12, '12', 'Grace Paseda', NULL, '1970s', 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Child Migration', 'Education', NULL, 'Nigeria', 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] Growing up with my family. I was told a lot that I am Nigerian. When we\'re at home, you\'re a Nigerian, but there was no explanation of what that entailed. So as far as I knew, I had a funny name and people took me out of that name and we ate different food. We didn\'t eat English food. And my parents spoke a different language, which I didn\'t understand because they didn\'t teach me that language. My mum god love her, used to wear. I mean, now it\'s really cool to wear traditional dress, African traditional dress to go out with the galley. Everyone knows what a galley is now, but in 1970 something, when you\'re going out with your mum, who\'s wrapped up in all these colored clothes, which no one wore and this big stiff thing on her head, and you\'ve got to go with her. I used to die.\n[00:00:59] I really did. I used to die so badly in terms of how I was brought up, how I saw myself. I was different. We were different. And later on, we immigrated to Nigeria and I stayed there for a couple of years. I was 13 and our parents hadn\'t taught us Yoruba, and they hadn\'t taught us many cultural things, such as the children do the cooking and the cleaning and the washing of the clothes. When we were here, my mum did that. Going to school there, they beat you a lot when you go and with the cane and we used to get the cane over here, but not as much as we\'d got it over there and you got beat for everything. And I got called English girl. Whereas when I was over here, I was called African there\'s a little song. I think a lot of people know it now just because of the volume of Nigerians here. But it, went\n[00:01:58] Oyinbo pepper! If you eat a pepper, you go yellow mummy, Oyinbo pepper. [00:02:05] It’s a little song that basically translates to, you can\'t eat pepper. If you eat pepper, you will scream for your mum because you\'re so English because we don\'t have pepper over here. So, they used to laugh at me.', 'Alienation;Culture;Ethnicity;Family;Food;Language;Music;Nigeria;Racism', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/11BwXY6tUIu7Rj9REBymFYxSU-yO_VlGG/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/drive/u/1/folders/1OrqUGGBtBLVlPbJm755H7KUWJOMGpKQU', 'Nanda', NULL, 0, 0),
(13, '13', 'Karamat Iqbal', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Kashmir;Pakistan', 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] Strongest memory that I have is from the first day I went to the school and I went to the school secretary\'s office and she\'s sent me to my classroom, and I arrived. And the teacher wasn\'t there, but the children were, there was a very tall white boy. He\'s big on little, probably kind of nervous because first day at the school, he greeted me by picking me up, forced me against the wall and said, we don\'t want any more fucking packis in this school and put me down. And everybody in the class laughed. I don\'t know whether the Pakistanian boys laughed, but they didn\'t intervene or anything. I tried to get my own back with this boy, if you just change one letter of his surname, it will be a swear word. So, I used to call him without pronunciation deliberately. If he says a word, my name isn\'t like that.\n[00:01:11] And I say, well, you know, English is not my first language, sorry. You know, probably doing it deliberately to call him an abusive name because I was getting my own back. This was a revenge. It\'s like the enemy and friend continuum. Those who abused me, I would say, were my enemy, but the others weren\'t necessarily my friend, I would say there were more common in the middle position near the throat. And the same with teachers, the teachers didn\'t call us by our names. In order of the times, it was only this particular teacher used to call us mush. I know, I remember him say, Oh, mush, come here. And I said to him, my name isn\'t mush. He said, what did you say? And I said, my name isn\'t mush.\n[00:02:02]\nSo, I was probably the first child to go to the head teacher to get a letter. So, I could start evening classes. Remember, evening classes are for adults. And if you\'re a child or at school, you cannot go because it would impact on your education. You will be too tired or what have you. But if you got a letter from your head teacher to say, I give my, this child my permission to attend evening classes, he can. So, I was attending the evening classes once a week to learn English. And the other thing I did was I discovered the local library and we didn\'t have libraries where I\'d come from, and this was a free library, and I could get up to four or five books. So, fell in love with reading from very early age, I\'d come to this country with a love for learning, always a child who never missed school in Kashmir, three years of traveling an hour there an hour back, I didn\'t miss a day. So, the one thing I brought with me was a love for learning, but also respect for learning there\'s education available and on benefit implement what we have here in this country is opportunity. We\'re talking 1970, when I came here and last year, 2017, I achieved my PhD. So Dr. Love for learning and our commitment to learning drove me and continues to drive me now.', 'Education;Kashmir;Language;Pakistan;Pride;Race;Racism', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1hbAN02VHqGOMC5nH-zjhAMqu8Ai15cQG/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/drive/u/1/folders/1OrqUGGBtBLVlPbJm755H7KUWJOMGpKQU', 'Nanda', NULL, 0, 0),
(14, '14', 'Lea', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Child Migration', NULL, NULL, 'Bulgaria', 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] My name is Lea, and I am from Bulgaria. I moved to the UK when I was seven years old and now, I am 10 years old. It all began when my dad had some work to do in London. He likes London a lot and suggested that it might be a good place for us to live. My dad came back to Bulgaria and my mum and dad discussed this and they decided to make the move to London. At Christmas that year me and my mum went to London for three weeks to see what it was like. And we really enjoyed it. I particularly like the shape of the people on the traffic lights. In Bulgaria, they were just stick people. Then I returned to Bulgaria and I lived with my mom for a few months while my dad was getting everything ready in London.\n\n[00:00:51] Finally, my mum went to London and I had to stay with my grandma and grandpa for a few months. Then my dad came back to get everything right at the end. He took me with him to London. We had a leaving party for friends and family in Bulgaria and I felt sad to leave but as soon as we were on the airplane, I felt very excited. When I moved to London, I didn\'t go straight to school as I was waiting for a place. So, I went to work with my dad who is a photographer. And then at the end of the day if there was time, he would take me to church Rube woods to play. Then I went to summer side school, but I didn\'t like it that much because I didn\'t feel so welcomed. But then I moved to ?. Children were so welcoming, and I had many friends and learned English quickly. Now I have close friends and feel very settled here. My English is fluent, and I am learning quickly. However, I do still miss my family in Bulgaria and look forward to visiting.', 'Assimilation;Bulgaria;Celebration;Education;Family;Language;Wellbeing', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1PMlvwx6IwVBh4ApL7ay6qdgMlFVZgSAD/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/drive/u/1/folders/1OrqUGGBtBLVlPbJm755H7KUWJOMGpKQU', 'Nanda', NULL, 0, 0),
(15, '15', 'Mais Peachey', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Iraq', 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] My great uncle was so hellbent that I was going to get a brilliant education, even though I couldn\'t even speak English, that they enrolled me into a very posh, private school, Catholic private school for girls. Of course. The weird thing about that was while everybody else was getting dropped off at school by their moms or dads, I was getting dropped off every single day by a black cab because nobody around to like pick me up and take me to school. My auntie, who I was living with had already had to leave to work every single morning. So, there was nobody to take me. My great uncle didn\'t drive. So, he would book a cab for me every morning and a cab in the afternoon to take me back, which was really, really weird as a child. So, imagine you\'re already having trouble fitting in because you don\'t speak the language and you\'re in an alien country.\n\n[00:00:56] Now there\'s a black cab that comes and drops you off every day, which is really odd. And I also get dropped off at home and have to spend a couple of hours by myself every day before my auntie would come home from work. I was really good at maths because maths, I think curriculum in Iraq was much more advanced at that level at that age than it was here. So, I did really well in maths, other subjects I struggled quite a bit, the struggle, the language, obviously, because I didn\'t really understand what they were teaching. So, every lunchtime, I had a portion of my lunchtime where I would be taken to the library by my form teacher and basically read children\'s books. And I absolutely loved that time. I loved it, I think for different reasons because I was given the attention that I wanted by somebody, somebody who was really, really sweet, absolutely lovely teacher called Mrs. Davis, who was my form tutor. We\'d sit there reading children\'s books for about half an hour, 20 minutes. Just to improve my reading. I remember that being one of the most comforting kind of nice times as well of my school experience.', 'Alienation;Assimilation;Class;Education;Family;Iraq;Language;Religion', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/123rgrtOlZrbg0jLFpOnOrPE-0d8z2eEy/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/drive/u/1/folders/1OrqUGGBtBLVlPbJm755H7KUWJOMGpKQU', 'Nanda', NULL, 0, 0),
(16, '16', 'Tew Bunnag', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Thailand', 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] In this school, I hadn\'t had a word of English when I got there. And I still remember very vividly what that felt like, you know, the whole foreignness of it, the whole being an outsider. And I think it marked me quite a lot, you know, the sense of being totally outside something and the urge to communicate as well and to understand what the hell was going on around me and to express myself. Anyway, I started learning English there with a teacher. It was a one-to-one and she was called Mrs. Evans. To this day I\'m grateful because I write in English and it definitely wasn\'t my first language, but it has become the language that I prefer to express myself in and writing. Mrs. Evans was not just an English teacher. I mean, she didn\'t come in sort of with a standard good morning.\n\n[00:01:05] How are you? What\'s her name? That kind of thing. But I remember the very first lesson. It was an initiation rather than a lesson because she mouthed these lines and got me to copy her and to listen to her and to try and pronounce and whatever word that I couldn\'t pronounce, which was just about all of them. She would help me, and she would exaggerate the movement of her mouth and her tongue, I remember, until I got it. And when I finished the lesson, I didn\'t understand what enough I had just done and what the words meant, but I could feel the music of the language and what she recited to me that day and got me to recite again, it\'s marked me as well in that sort of worldview kind of way was a poem by William Blake, which goes ‘To see a World in a Grain of Sand and a Heaven in a Wildflower,\nHold Infinity in the palm of your hand And Eternity in an hour.’\n\n [00:02:19] Well, at the end of that lesson, I somehow managed to recite it. And I went home that evening. I remember, and my mother said, what did you learn today? As mothers do. I said, I learned this, and she was blown away. And she said, do you know what it means? And I said, no. And then she explained it to me in Thai. And it was beautiful that it was a beautiful vision of being alive. Really. So, I\'m grateful to Mrs. Evans. And then gradually, I remember other poems as well, Ts. Elliot. I think she gradually built in the, \'Good morning. How are you bud?\' But always she emphasized the sound, the music of English. And it, I fell in love with, I fell in love with this new language, with language learning. There was another English lesson as well, which was a class full of kids.\n\n[00:03:20] And it was taken by the headmaster\'s wife. And this one was the, your standard sort of, you know, reading out sentences and stuff. And it was a very strange class because I don\'t remember the details of the class, but it must\'ve learned something of course. But what I did learn was how wacky England was or English psyche or whatever it is you want to call it. The strange thing was that at the end of this class, this lady was called Mrs. Stanford. Actually, she used to subtly point towards a Japanese girl I remember, who sat in the front row and the Japanese girl would disappear behind this door. And then she\'d come back with a tin box of biscuits. The first time I observed this, I thought, what is going to happen now? The others seem to know, you know, but most of them, anyway, they seem to know what was going on or pretended to, but I certainly didn\'t.\n\n[00:04:22] And Mrs. Dunford would make this kind of a ritual of very slowly opening the box. And then the Japanese girl would hold the lid. And Mrs. Stanford would pour in these chocolate biscuits that were like fingers, you know, the long ones. And then she would take the lid back from the Japanese girl and she would start rattling it. And at that moment it was the cue for all of us to do this very strange thing, which, because we gradually, of course we did it without thinking we did it because we thought this is what we had to do with it was to go (whistles) \'chocolate biscuits\'! And of course, this all came out because we all came from different countries, Japan, Germany and Chile and Thailand and whatever, you know, it all came out with various (strange?) pronunciations. So this was the end of my standard English class. (Whistles) \'Chocolate biscuits!\'', 'Alienation;Assimilation;Chile;Education;Family;Food;Germany;Japan;Language;Music;Pride;Thailand', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/11VG_wuTZt650D3p2N6y55XSNyZ7CmQZa/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/drive/u/1/folders/1OrqUGGBtBLVlPbJm755H7KUWJOMGpKQU', 'Nanda', NULL, 0, 0),
(18, '18', 'Canay and Abdul (Barbero)', NULL, NULL, 'Video', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Denmark;Turkey;Zambia', 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:00] Canay: What’s your name?\nAbdul: I’m Abdul.\nCanay: Nice meeting you Abdul my name is Canay\nAbdul: You too. You know what, I love my beard.\nCanay: You love it? Okay I’ll just tidy it up with scissors then.\n[00:00:10] Abdul: Yeah, it’s like a man’s makeup you know. Officially I’m half Danish and Zambian. I bet you still hear the accent huh?\nCanay: Yeah, you still got the accent.\nAbdul: When I’m with my European half, I have to kind of like play out a different character. It’s really weird. And, when I’m with my other African half I have to play another different character again. So, I think a lot of people here, a lot of young ones in my situation have got like an identity crisis because of this. I won’t lie, I did too at one point in my life.\n[00:00:41] Canay: Well, my background is Turkish but I was born and raised in London. I do go to Turkey once a year to see family, but London feels like home.\n[00:00:55] Abdul: I don’t understand, flame my ears?\nCanay: Yeah, it’s a very old school, traditional Turkish. It just burns all the fluff off the cheeks and ears.\n[00:00:55] Canay: The air is changing. We have a lot of Romanian, Albanian, Turkish and English customers.\nThis is a traditional Turkish massage. Deep breath of the nose..', 'Alienation;Culture;Denmark;Ethnicity;Family;Race;Turkey;Wellbeing;Zambia', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1QVE-kxlJKU0liXk_iu6IYR7eVAXwSP8EMHGo1w8wJKE/edit?usp=sharing', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1l8rLv12sYQYyci9srsnNwLuWR7vFReHQ/view?usp=sharing', 'Celia', NULL, 0, 0),
(19, '19', 'Eran and Matthew (International Hair for Men)', NULL, '1950s', 'Video', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Cyprus;Hungary;Turkey', 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:00] Matthew: My dad’s Welsh and my mum’s Hungarian. Eran: Oh wow!\nMatthew: She came over in 1956 when she was young. Eran: 1956?\nMatthew: Yeah, there was like an uprising against the Soviet Union there and her and her family must have, like, left. My grandad, like, his brother, both their wives and their two, both their two oldest kids. I think they had about four kids there and they were all just living on the kitchen floor, like, just sleeping. It’s something that you don’t really picture these days, you know.\n[00:00:37] What about you? Whereabouts are you from?\nEran: My parents, they’re from Cyprus. They’re both from the Turkish side. Matthew: Oh, Turkish side? When did they come, what year? Do you know?\nEran: Probably... I’m not sure exactly the year but it was probably around the sixties, seventies. Some people will come to London and they will not try to learn another language but there are some people who will learn the language. Matthew: Do you speak Turkish at home as well?\nEran: I can do a little bit if my mum asks me something and she will ask me in Turkish, like “Make me a chai.” You know, I’ll be like OK. Chai means tea, you know. Kahve means coffee. It’s a nice language, to speak to Turkish. But, with every language it is nice to speak. [00:01:30] Do you watch UFC? Matthew: Oh, you know what, I was working last night so I missed the match.\nEran: You mean, the McGregor…?\nMatthew: Yeah. Eran: McGregor was, you know, he’s been talking a lot and acting.\nMatthew: Yeah, that’s what I’ve heard as well. Eran: Like the big shot and Khabib just put him in his place. He took the fight to him. They escorted Khabib out and then put him back in the ring, it was all mayhem! Even Drake, you know the famous rapper, he was in the crowd and he was shocked as he jumped up.', 'Assimilation;Cyprus;Ethnicity;Family;Food;Hungary;Language;Politics;Sport;Turkey', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1wrXwzL-vYzYOu5fwhRYh2JVTLedv3rxFH1bYO5KpnI8/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1-Lj6fwqF5XXJNb1yMppjadLMCGiw-A-z/view?usp=sharing', 'Celia', NULL, 0, 0),
(20, '20', 'Anuar and Joaquin (Slim\'s Barbers)', NULL, NULL, 'Video', 'Immigration', 'Child Migration', 'Education', NULL, 'Morocco;Spain', 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:00] Anuar: I’m originally from Morocco. Joaquin: Morocco, very nice. Anuar: Yeah. Joaquin: I’m from Spain. Anuar: Okay, okay, our neighbour. Yeah I came here, went to junior school. Our school was very diverse and very mixed. It’s like a United Nations school, you know?\nJoaquin: Yeah, yeah. [00:00:17] Anuar: Everyone just gets on. And everyone gets along because we coan all link, you know– All of our parents were the first immigrants and we came after, kinda thing, you know? So we could all relate.\n[00:00:31] Anuar: The hardest thing was to actually learn the language, cause I spoke– Joaquin: Oh really?\nAnuar: Yeah. Eleven-year-old speaking Arabic and French in Morocco and all of a sudden, a new language.\n[00:00:47] Joaquin: We’ve counted fifty-seven different nationalities that they come regularly here.\nAnuar: That’s lovely, that’s good.\nJoaquin: And there is all sort of people. Today we’ve done the, a new, a new nationality. He was from South Korea. And you know, and this guy, he was a student.\n[00:01:06] Joaquin: We’ve got a world map. And we got this just to do something with our clients, like put a map, and you can put a pin in every country that you’ve done as a client. Countries you haven’t done, you can through Instagram, invite those people from those countries to come and have a haircut for free, or whatever.\nAnuar: Whoa.\n[00:01:27] Anuar: Okay so you’re not just a barber you’re a global barber! Anuar (in Arabic): الأوروبي عنده الساعة و العربي عنده الوقت\nJoaquin: Okay.\nAnuar: It means the European has the watch, but the Arab has the time.\n(both laugh)\n[00:01:47] Anuar: Mister global, who cuts hair like he’s mister noble, yeah, he gives it to you and there’s no trouble, yeah, come back again he won’t cut your hair for the double. Joaquin: Thank you.\nAnuar: Okay.', 'Assimilation;Community;Culture;Education;Friends;Language;Morocco;Spain', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1oLwNakFMT2fouSNnG1d4I8aCH9DNrFMcnyrMd2rNxOo/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1AI2cHOz7fQqbpksYLH3XHS0w-nQme6bG/view?usp=sharing', 'Kaytie', NULL, 0, 0),
(21, '21', 'Valcie', NULL, '1960s', 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Child Migration', NULL, NULL, 'Jamaica', 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:07] I came from Jamaica when I was eight years old. So my memory would be my grandmother gratering, my grandfather gr– had loads of corn, and I remember all the colors of the corn, it was like um, purple, uh yellow, all colors in one corn. And then my grandmother would select certain corn, and she would grater the corn. [00:00:30] And we had a little knife that would peel the ginger so fine to take off all the um, the skin of the ginger. And then she’d be gratering the corn and that remembered was making hominy porridge with grated, fresh grated coconut, and it was like with cow’s milk, there was no pasteurisation, just straight from the cow, because literally our cow lived in the same place where we lived, just behind the house. [00:00:54] And remembered my grandmother that sweetened it. And our sugar would come from the cane. And we used to watch it being cooked outside in an open fire. The fire underneath would be bubbling up, and my grandmother would be stirring it. And then you, you just see all the corn, just you hear them popping sometimes, and then we’d just watch it cook for about an hour. [00:01:20]\nMy mother came here, she left me as a young, literally as a baby I think. Then, so my grandmother had loads of grandchildren that she looked after. Our daily life was really different because as children, we would get up in the morning, do what we need to do around the house, and you know get ourselves ready, and then we’ll go off for the day. [00:01:44]\nGoing off for the day would be somewhere down in the valley where the coffee beans grow, deep down, because it was quite like, quite rainforesty down there. Because you could be down– there’s a canopy, you could not even see the sky. [00:01:57]\nIt was so nice. Because I remembered eating the, the cocoa beans, before the coffee. So I think I must have been quite high on caffeine all those times you know, because before the coffee becomes coffee the beans are quite sweet. I don’t know if it was coffee or cocoa, but I remember eating quite a lot of it. You don’t– I used to just suck it off and stuff because it was really sweet. [00:02:20]\nAnd I remember getting up in the morning, and then I’d going behind the houses, and where the the ginger plant were growing, and I used to get all the dew. It tastes just like ginger because of all the dew would settle in there and there was quite a lot of dew and I remember drinking that. I thought it was really nice. That’s one of my earliest memory really. [00:02:40]\nBut as children, you see, we were very much outdoors children, there was no indoors, ‘cause in fact, you would only be indoors if you were going to sleep. [00:02:49]\nThe grass behind the house used to grow so high, but it was on a slope. And I remember just going there, sitting in the sun, and uh, plaiting the grass, and just lying there looking up into the sky. Ah, so lovely.\n[00:03:04]\nUp until I was eight years old, I was daily climbing trees. We’d climb up there because we might see a fruit at the top that we particularly like. And we’d go up there and go and get the fruit. And come down, never a problem. We’ll fall down, we’ll burn ourselves, we play with fire and do all the fire things but we never um, we never, you know, we’re quite rough– rough, you know, quite, tough. [00:03:04]\nCompared to how I see these children grow in this country I think I had a fantastic childhood, when I look at it. [00:03:41]\nThe 28th of January, I came here. 1968. And absolutely freezing. And my grandmother had made our clothes, and it was a very thin, very thin linen blue, navy blue, me and my sister had it. A suit. It was a little skirt, pleated skirt and a little jacket. It was so cold. And that when we were on the plane, when we sort of, when the temperature changed, they gave us some blankets, and I remember it was British Airway. And we had these blankets, and it wasn’t even warm enough.\n[00:04:14]\nAnd when I came– uh, where did we move?– came to Stoke Newington, the houses were so cold, everything was freezing, and I couldn’t– there was no leaves on the trees. And when the summer came, and I’m, and I’m asking them, which trees are these, which fruit grows on these trees? And they just looked at me, there was no fruit trees. ‘Cause no fruit trees grow on the roadside. And that was the worst wake up call when I realized that you couldn’t go out to play. [00:04:43]\nMy mum made me cook from an early age, because you see, the thing is, me and my sister came, and there were already three children here already. So, the fact is, from an early age, I was looking after them. It meant that I’m always in the kitchen, and being the oldest, it meant that I was always in the kitchen with my mum. [00:05:01]\nFirst it’s watching, first it’s, I started by chopping little bits, she would give me onions, and stuff, and then I’ll be starting to, my job now is to start to wash the rice, and I could never get it right. I mean and she’s getting quite angry because I would waste loads of rice, and she didn’t have a lot of rice to waste. So, yeah. And then, once I got used to the hang of making rice, and then she will give me a dish to make, and then if I get it wrong, she will get upset because that got wasted and nobody else could eat it. And I think my childhood pretty much ended when I left Jamaica. [00:05:36]\nThe freedom, the space, the open air, and when I came here everything is, it’s just closed in. Ah, of course, eventually you grow to, uh, you bring the memories with you. So my memory with me was of food.', 'Alienation;Culture;Family;Food;Jamaica;Wellbeing', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1TmeOdHWNTMn_IxKQjOWeL7syvVOvulQllQYlN1JJwZ4/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/13V7bstXAm1MkQPJzzYNCeO4o-w7-385A/view', 'Kaytie', NULL, 0, 0);
