(22, '22', 'Dani', NULL, '1960s', 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Economic', NULL, NULL, 'Spain', 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:00] My mum and dad came to the UK in the late 60s, early 70s from, northwestern Spain— a region called Galicia.\n[00:00:12]\nThey didn’t speak any English, and they’ve told me many times how tough it was in the beginning to, you know, settle in and understand the culture— and, yeah they started working, you know, very menial low-income jobs.\n[00:00:30]\nUh, my dad was a chef in a hotel and my mum was a cleaner. Eventually they were given the opportunity to rent a cafe in Oxford called St Giles’ Cafe, which they ran for over twenty-five years— British greasy spoon cafe. [00:00:51]\nYeah, I have a strong affinity to a very traditional, kind of working class British food, which, you know, means a lot to me, and I think will always be a part of, my personal identity as someone born in the UK to migrant parents.\n[00:01:13]\nAs an only child, my parents, you know, their aim was to give me a future, that they never had, and, seven days a week from six in the morning, they’d get up, ‘til seven in the evening when they’d get home. And from the moment they opened til the moment they closed, there would be a queue to the door with all of the tables full and it’s quite amazing, that sort of two people that come from extraordinarily humble, difficult backgrounds with no education, and a tough poor upbringing, and family situation could come to the UK and, and work their socks off doing something that was distinctly British in character and build a life for themselves. You know, a happy, stable life.\n[00:02:13]\nIt was just the best. It was the best cafe. You know, I loved going there in the morning and having my breakfast before school and, it was, it was my home. The Full English Breakfast would be my death row meal, for sure.\n[00:02:30]\nTwo fried eggs on two toasts, with three or four slices of really amazing British bacon, with two or three sausages, with beans, maybe a fried tomato— that would’ve been my favorite combination, with a cup of tea, and yeah there’s all— many different approaches to the Full English, many different bite combinations, whether you’re going, just egg with the bacon, or egg with the sausage, or are you going egg, bacon, sausage, and some beans—\n[00:03:10]\nFor me it was just, like, every mouthful is just a source of joy and deliciousness.\n[00:03:20]\nOne time me and my mum tried to calculate how much of each of the ingredients my dad would have cooked over the years that he was there. And I think, like over twenty-five years, he cooked, like, seven hundred and fifty thousand eggs, nearly two million rashers of bacon, and two million sausages, and it became a bit of a crazy idea, really, that he did that, but, you know, he did.\n[00:03:50]\nAt that time in history, labour migration was a lot less than it is now, and it was hard for them to begin with, but, you know, it was their attitude, and that’s the thing I kind of feel about the UK, or at least the version of the UK that I felt I grew up in, is that you take on the British mentality, and you know how to do things, how to improve and how to move forward, and there’s no doubt that if you were to ask my mum and dad where their home is, I’m pretty sure they would say Oxford.', 'Assimilation;Class;Commerce;Culture;Family;Food;Gallicia;Pride;Spain;Third person;Work', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1YDCeHObU0XWTJtv8iKFb5zOiFRSvdTZ0kYpj6mbZ9Ls/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1712_zIg0JZwM57rW-auJTfEAV42VOHem/view?usp=sharing', 'Kaytie', NULL, 0, 0),
(23, '23', 'Ela', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Poland', 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:55] When my mum was alive what would happen when I come to visit, and\nsometimes I would come once a year to Poland, but each time I would come my mum would\nmake the cake for me. And each time I would leave, my mum would make a cake and I\nwould take this cake and I would also, “oh don’t make it, don’t make it” but she would insist\non making it. And then, I would come to my house in London and the first thing I would do I\nwould eat the cake and sometimes I would eat nothing else for two days, but this cake. And\nit almost had this kind of quality of healing, of carrying my mum’s energy, my mum’s love,\nmy mum’s care into the country that I was very much without her, without anybody really.\n\n[00:01:25] It’s made with yeast. So, the yeast have to stay covered with a bit of flour, sugar\nand milk – warm milk, to warm up and to rise, yeah? And then all the windows in the house\nhas to be closed because there has to be even temperature or else, throughout the flat.\nBecause otherwise, the cake can get a cold.\n\n[00:01:40] My mum made such a fuss about it. I remember as a young girl she would just\nlike shout and say, “Don’t open the door, don’t open the window, don’t open anything. Stop\nrunning around here, the cake is here. The cake is here!” The cake took a personality.\n\n[00:02:19] So when the yeast rises, you have a flour in a big bowl. There’s a lot of eggs in it,\nmainly yolks. And you mix everything with your hands – that’s how my mum did. Butter,\nvanilla, maybe some raisins, or sultanas, orange peel is very important and then the biggest\nwork is making the cake. You have this huge round bowl and you just make it, make it, make\nit, make it, make it, make it, knead it, knead it, you know.\n\n[00:02:46] And then you cover it with a linen cloth. And then you leave it to rise again in a\ntin. You make kruszonka – it’s like a crumble to put on top with this butter, sugar and flour.\nAnd then you bake it in the oven and of course you check every now and then if it’s ready.\nYou have to not open it for the first fifteen minutes because then it will collapse. And then\nyou hope it doesn’t burn up at the bottom.\n\n[00:03:03] The cake was just delicious. When it comes out, she wouldn’t let us eat it straight\naway. It has to cool. Basically, you could eat two pieces of the cake and feel really good and\nrounded. I mean it tastes like the best of my mum.\n\n[00:03:50] I think here the key is, this kind of transition from travelling from one country to\nanother. The country I left into the country I’m living. And really, I’m in this homeless spot\nbecause I’m never, I’m never going to be English. I don’t even want to be English. But I do\nnot fully feel at home here. I do not fully feel at home in Poland. The cake is like a something\nto help me through. Basically, the cake is part of her and that’s the way she expresses love\nto me. And that’s the way I have a bit of protection, a bit of her… her love.', 'Alienation;Family;Food;Poland;Wellbeing', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Sn0XagM6WJFsLraaaAC3-qxHJuk-W7ceXwNKdSaaJmE/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1p-jfuxR2uVgEZu66ryFUU_DR2X2TSf3I/view?usp=sharing', 'Mariri', NULL, 0, 0),
(24, '24', 'Ilika', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Education', 'Economic', NULL, 'India', 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:01:02] My name is Ilika and I’m from India. I’m basically from Darjeeling. I\ncame from a small town and when I moved to high school, I moved to a convent in\nDarjeeling. I was the first to move out of home. And for my graduation I went to Kolkata and\nfor my masters I was in Delhi. For my MPhil, and Ph.D. I was in Bombay. So, I have\ncontinuously been out of my hometown and my own little sheltered, you know, spot. So, I\nhave been quite adaptable that way. So, when I moved to the UK, it wasn’t very different in\nthe sense that it was a different country, the weather was so different from tropical sunny\nIndia, but apart from that I didn’t have any problem because I knew the language well. I had\nread a lot of English stories and you know novels and stuff, so I kind of knew about the pubs.\nI kind of knew about the English countryside. I was very adaptable with the food. So, you\nknow I think those are the four things; the language and the food which comes in force\nwhen you move into a place.\n\n[00:01:34] The first place where I came when I set foot in England was in Leicestershire and\nthen my husband was moved to Birmingham and then I was more than delighted because\nHinckley was basically quite a boring place for me at that time. There wasn’t much\nhappening. We had to go to Leicester, I remember we used to go to these Gujarati shops\nto get our spices and our pickles and our poppadoms. Whereas Hinckley was so English and\nwe also felt a bit of racial, you know, undercurrent there.\n\n[00:02:32] In India, we wear salwar kameez which is like a tight pajama with a loose top. I\nwas wearing one and I was out in Hinkley, and there were three four English boys, teenagers\nyou know. They were in a car and they were eating food and one of them threw a piece of\nsausage at me and shouted, “You Paki!”. My husband’s colleagues used to face a lot of\nproblem in Hinckley, you know. When coming back from work late, people on the streets\nused to say, “you Indians have taken our jobs away!”. And then when we moved to\nBirmingham, it was such a wonderful change. I felt that it was a big city. There was a lot\nmore happening, it was multicultural. There were people from all different places. And I\nmean, I went to English homes and you know, I had good neighbours, you know. They\ntaught me baking so it all started with food. And food was so easy to get along with people,\nyou know.\n\n[00:03:19] For me, the monsoon is synonymous with the Kitchari because it makes me\nnostalgic and reminds me of home. And in England again, it’s raining all the time so any\nseason is Kitchari season. Putting what is available in the house and every Indian house\nwould have the rice, and the dhal and potatoes. Where I am from, Darjeeling, it rains a lot.\nWhen the monsoon comes it continues for days. And I remember I‘ve seen that in my\nchildhood, my parents can’t go to the market because it’s raining so hard, and those\ndownpours are like really heavy downpours. So, I mean I’ve often heard my mother say,\n“there is no vegetables, what should we do, should we do Kitchari?”\n\n[00:04:00] So off you go, it’s raining outside and there is this hot, bubbling Kitchari cooking\nin the pot and the family sitting all around together, these days you have chinaware, you\nknow stuff, but in traditional Indian homes, people used to have, in the olden days, on leaf\nplates and when you actually put that Kitchari and you can see the steam coming, and the \naroma. Even better if you are living in a house which has a tin correlated roof. You know the\npitter patter of the rain drops, and you can hear the frogs cloaking. I mean there is nothing\nmore romantic and deeply routed to my Bengali culture and the association with the rains\nand the poetry and the literature and Kitchari.\n\n[00:04:00] Now, when we have Hindu ceremonies, we cook the Kitchari for the gods, and\nin addition to that we do five kinds of fried items which go as an offering to the gods with\nthe Kitchari. Those fries either can be a potato, cauliflower, aubergine or eggplant, beans,\nspinach leaves fried. No eggs and no omelettes, no meat. You know, that doesn’t go.\nSometimes, we also have poppadom. And we put a drop of ghee on the hot Kitchari\nwhich spreads on the plate and we add pickles as well. It reminds me of my culture and my\nroots and my background and my home – my home country. And I think, no matter\nwherever you travel, which part of the world you go to, you carry a bit of your roots in\nyourself. And I think food also brings the family together.\n\n[00:06:00] So we are sitting as a family, in England far away from the monsoon rains back\nhome in India. And I think it’s connected a bit with nostalgia as well. You chat over it and\nsometimes your hands dry up. Traditional Indian food is always had using your hands and\nKitchari even if it is hot and spread out of the plate, we still have it with our hands. The\nwhole joy of licking your fingers and gloopy thing on your, you know, and the plate drying\nup when you’ve finished your meal but you still want to sit and talk as a family. All that adds\nto the romanticism of the food in itself. The important bit is how you eat it as well, not just\nthe taste. So, I think Kitchari that way is simple but it gives you all the right aromas and the\ningredients and the nostalgia and the method of eating and everything together is a very\nwholesome package in itself.', 'Alienation;Celebration;Culture;Family;Food;Language;Pride;Racism;Religion;Wellbeing', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1SZ1pDNky0fWyXReoIwlVfKCwGi989lustnPANZ8UdT0/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1SgsfebLiPz-zCSN341YutRIi6QZafilo/view?usp=sharing', 'Mariri', NULL, 0, 0),
(25, '25', 'Raj', NULL, '1970s', 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Economic', 'Child Migration', NULL, 'India', 'RTB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:20] Indian food, you can eat everyday because it’s proper, yeah?\n[00:00:42] I am here with my mum who has been in the UK for over 40 years. She came over when she was eight years old, my dad came over when he was in his early twenties. And they\nsettled in the midlands and basically raised three children in the British Sikh community.\n[00:01:02] And today we are sitting around this table and we are enjoying a sort of Sunday\nlunch traditional particularly within the Punjabi community called aloo parathas with achar, mango pickle, natural yogurt and butter.\n[00:00:58] Usually we make it on Sunday. Because everybody family is at home- children,\nmother, father. Day off…\n[00:01:07] You got the whole family on Sunday. Did you use to have it on Sundays when you\nwere a kid, mum?\n[00:01:12] Yes.\n[00:01:13] Yeah, so it’s like a tradition basically.\n[00:01:14] Yes.\n[00:01:16] We are from the farming community. And in India, even I think with schools, you\nonly get Sundays off. So, Sundays are the only time where you can get to spend the day as a\nfamily at home basically. So, when you were little, mum, did nanny used to make it for you?\n[00:02:19] Yeah. Nanny used to make, your grandmother used to make it very nice. That’s\nwhy I learn it from her. I was, I think how many years old…when I learn everything from my\nmum. My father say, only bring two children. We were four sisters, one brother. You know\nwhat my grandfather said in India, my mum and dad, “no way”. He said “here, take the\nmoney and he sold his land. Give it to his daughter. Nobody will look after your children\nhere. Please take all children. That I never forget my grandfather – he said that. Never.\n[00:02:32] When I moved from here, I didn’t like the smell. I didn’t like it, even on the\nairport, the smell. I mean something like a spray, like that you know. When you come in new-\n[00:02:31] Like a disinfectant or something?\n[00:02:35] You don’t know what the spray is on and everything. The people clean. Heathrow\nairport was very nice and clean that time. But smell come in, it was (?) and I was (?). I was\nwearing Indian suit, like this, yeah? It was March and my dad and uncle brought a taxi. They\npicked up our stuff and put it in the taxi because the snow was that much. Some people\ndon’t remember these things but I still remember.\n[00:03:40] When I came here, my mum used to live somewhere else. Children used to live\nin somebody else’s house – few, few months. It was very hard times. Shopping was very\nexpensive. We were four to five children. Very, very expensive. My dad used to get twenty-\nfive pound and my mom used to get fifteen pound on airport. It was very hard times that I\ncan’t forget it.\n[00:04:00] English people used to not let us sit with English people at school. They used to\ntake us separate. To teach us how to eat the food, how to talk, it was a special school that\ntime.\n[00:04:09] Did you like the English food though, when you first tried it? What did you like?\n[00:04:10] No, few months I didn’t like it. It was chips, you know. Every food chips and the\npeas and fish, you know. And we were not used to that.\n[00:04:53] I think one of the things I noticed, when we were young, particularly my dad,\nbecause he if quite traditional, I remember him saying to mum don’t feed the kids chips all\nthe time. And even know when I go back home, he asks me questions like do you make roti\nat home, basically which is chapati. Cause he wants to make sure that I am staying in touch\nwith my culture, and that’s when I have to say to reassure him that although I’m not making\nit here it doesn’t mean that I definitely don’t want to make it, it’ s just that there is no point\nin me making all of that dough just for one person ‘cause it’s a waste.\n[00:06:03] Lot of people in the come to London because we are all economic migrants,\nreally. I think at first, I didn’t appreciate the culture and community aspect. When you are in\nyour twenties you finish your schooling and your studies and you want to go to London and\nmake something of yourself. Get that experience. I think that in my thirties, I began to\nappreciate what I was missing. I started feeling a little bit more isolated from my family. It\nwasn’t as hard as when I used to be with my sister, basically. Because it felt like a family\nmember was here. I could still speak Punjabi, make Punjabi food. Now I’m feeling it more\nbecause I’m working with people who aren’t from my particular community with those\nexperiences. So, there are times when it can get a bit suffocating. That’s what got me\nthinking that food plays an important part in doing that, in helping you to kind of stay\ngrounded. Because I think that’s what my parents do, my family and my parents help me to\nstay grounded, you know in the kind of contemporary society we live in basically and the\nsort of pressures we have.\n[00:06:18] She lives really far away. Sometimes I feel I didn’t let them go away for all my life\nyeah. But when she came, and my other daughter came, I cried so much.\n[00:06:23] Stop getting upset mum, you are making me upset.\n[00:06:56] I don’t want to let them go away from me. But I don’t have that many objections\nbecause they want to do job here. Sometimes when I go on Sunday, I feel it. They want to\nstay here. But I haven’t got a choice, you know. But she’s so far away now – alone. I feel so\nmuch for her. That’s why I say if you are tired from there come to me no problem.\n[00:06:59] Well that’s what I’m going to do, mum.\n[00:07:09] The five-bedroom house is empty. you come and find a job here. We are not\nlooking for a lot of money. We are looking for love.', 'Alienation;Community;Culture;Education;Family;Food;Religion;Third Person;Wellbeing', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1_ninn04y0OIp7SxXWqIq5GeFt18XdF6qhuvAwEtrK80/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1Zpo7QdTspdV4EdI2lTNgpNf1LiLJ2DgW/view?usp=sharing', 'Mariri', NULL, 0, 0),
(26, '26', 'Annah Felton', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', NULL, 'Education', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:00] I am Annah Felton, and I work as part of a group hour. The one thing for me that really sort of blew my mine is going back out of the camp for numeral occasions, where [0:10] actually how many students I met who were volunteering at the camp. I am being a university actor myself and we very sort of brought home that sort of power of youth and change [00:20]. And this kind of hope for the future. And this generation of… Of students being more aware of politics, religions. And that part of communication [00:30] and a lot of them sort of blogging at themselves. Telling other people what they had been doing. And this real movement of youth and energy. And a lot of work we do [00:40], we sort of meet people that want to change the world and help. And yes do your getting away through a lack of organizations. And… But I think if a young person is [00:50] guided to the right structure and the right organizations to help. They can be a great energy that putting to a project. And sort of learn from that. From life experience [01:00] to tell those children who tell those children…', 'Education;Politics;Pride;Religion;Work', '', '#26 CMBMN Anna Felton - Google Docs', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1LG_cMPsnT8-Ir2dlkMQVHDQVj14p1XRB/view?usp=sharing', 'Marie-Aude', NULL, 0, 0),
(27, '27', 'Abi (1)', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Emigration', 'Refugee/Asylum', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] We decided to set up a vaccination clinic because MSF was starting to get involved with treating people. So if we… we thought we could do something preventative and vaccination centre could be a way to do that and… There is so many nationalities there. And it was just kind of impossible to figure out what everybody vaccination status was. So, we thought that influence was a real strength in Europe in the winter and the people in the camp will never have the opportunity to be vaccinated or have been exposed to influencer before. And it’s a vaccine everybody can have, all ages, or there is just something of small amount of people that would not be able to have the vaccine. So, it was consistent, it was fair… and everybody had the opportunity to get that. So we vaccinated against influenza and then earlier on this year there was the start of a measles outbreak and I think it was about 20 people which I had know with measles. So we very quickly work with the French Health Minister and MSF to do it were very short but substantial measles vaccination program. And at least we Vaccinate. The out break didn’t spread. It kind of stop any strucks. Which was good. Because it would have been very.. dangerous.', 'Ethnicity;France;Healthcare;Politics', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1qCJlEhsrVQDBoY-x8K9eewhmjEBLj_EBTa9Zi0pI5Ko/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1Y2FR2Hr89bZ6_JCYMbZSylUR7KS1ZqsM/view', 'Marie-Aude', NULL, 0, 0),
(28, '28', 'Abi (2)', NULL, '2020s', 'Audio', 'Emigration', 'Refugee/Asylum', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[00:0001] Most people has upper respiratory infections known as a jungle cough, most people had a cough which develops from some people into pneumonia. Lot of skins problems [00:10] because of the cold and the damp. And, not able to wash clothes because of a lot of escapees. And just general kind of cold [00:20] and restlessness and lot of aching joints and bones and… There is also a lot of trauma, of bruising [00:30], fractures, black eyes, head injuries from the police violence. That was a lot of the things that we saw. **********In the vaccination centre, we just focused on doing the vaccine and we directed most people to MSF. But we did a lot of first state. And [00:50] changing interest in things like that. And a lot of referrals were made by MSF to hospital. For people with fractured bones and things like that.', 'Healthcare;War', '', '#28 CMBMN Abi - Google Docs', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/17iuVZfoaHts9lkKNP21a1Ypm8IZ1eU2I/view?usp=sharing', 'Marie-Aude', NULL, 0, 0),
(29, '29', 'Abi (3)', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Emigration', 'Refugee/Asylum', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] Maybe my training as a paramedic has been quite good at being able to just power through and day to day just deal with things rather than get too emotional about it but it obviously accumulates.\n[00:00:14] And for me personally, because I was juggling a full time job back in London and going to Cali. Going backwards and forwards the whole time, it just got incredibly exhausting and having to change mindset from working in the jungle to working in London every week or so. I think I got quite emotional because I was tired.\n[00:00:33] Now I’m back and I’ve had a chance to kind of have my feet in one place for more than a few days, you feel guilty it’s that survivors guilt you’re not there to help. But actually it’s important to realise that you know if I’m burnt out and tired and emotional then I can’t help, so it’s good just to be back and get my head straight before kind of maybe going back later.', 'Community;Education;France;Healthcare;Wellbeing', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1tfFMjdFj9eii9UQkDb4ufrzLizIc-iKrb89nNwH7KOA/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1uvkXzLKadsaP1zSAPZIcLGEQXmQdXu6r/view', 'Yasmeen', NULL, 0, 0),
(30, '30', 'Abi (4)', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Emigration', 'Refugee/Asylum', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] The media wasn’t sympathetic to the situation, it was kind of demonised and you’re working in the conditions where the media portrayed you as helping terrorists and all sorts of horrible things. The people you were helping were criminalised, you didn’t have the support and we didn’t know what we were doing. So it was quite stressful, but I think I’ve learnt more in the last 6 months about life than the last 27 years. \n[00:00:30] I was awarded the association of ambulance chief executive for outstanding service as a paramedic for the work in Cali. That was very humbling. I was very shocked but very honoured to get that award out of the whole country. But I felt that there were volunteers out there who deserved so many awards, that I felt like I shouldn’t be the one with the award it should be for everybody. But I was very honoured to get that.', 'Alienation;France;Healthcare;Pride;Wellbeing', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/11F9-Y7DERrzm2KsJsLANAd0BFeJ7vs2OqT0XxihTXZg/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1Mi5HtvC5iLb4yS5OZqr1i5TdPi_e6Dah/view', 'Yasmeen', NULL, 0, 0),
(31, '31', 'Afghani Voices', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Refugee/Asylum', NULL, NULL, 'Afghanistan;Iraq', 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] (Man 1) You know we here Regency England, it is a dream country for us. Everybody’s talking about London, London, London, London, so we are thinking yeah let’s try it. How is London, how is looking, how is the work, how is the weather, how the people are there. You know that’s why they are trying to go over there and make a good life there. [00:00:22] I want to live, I don’t want to die. London is not important for me, life is important for me. Over there it’s a multicultural country yeah and there’s a lot of Afghani, Pakistani community over there, so for us its for the better. And also we speak English, we don’t know about French or Dutch or other languages. We learn English from the start of school, so it’s better for us because we also have relatives over there. [00:00:51] It’s really difficult here because when we go out, we know the people they don’t like us and also the language. And also look at this area, you know they’re giving us no facilities and even the people there they ask for asylum over there. I have a few mates from Afghanistan, they put asylum and they even didn’t take them to the court, to the judge, they just refused them. They’re going to refuse the letter. Before it was good, now we have problems over there, that’s why we came here. [00:01:21] (Man 2) I’m trying to go to England. If I find any chance, I would like to go to England. If not I will stay in or I will go to another country. It is dangerous but we have to try. It’s not dangerous more than Afghanistan. There is so many problems in Afghanistan, not only the Taliban. There’s so many other dangers in Afghanistan that we cannot stay. [00:01:48] (Man 3) I will stay now here in France, I now stay here, I like France. Everything is here. No other country, no London, no anything, I don’t like. Camp and here same, same life. [00:02:00] (Woman 1) I was living in Iraq, in Daquq. My city Izwar between Daijahn army Qulish so my house is brushing there, so no have any life in there. Because we left Iraq, we come to here and to buy lorry to another city we come to here. we want to go to England because England is better. [00:02:24] In Iraq if you finish school it won’t mean anything because school is just for rich pupil, for government cousin. I have finished school but I don’t be anything. So my sister is finishing school and she won’t be anything. They don’t have any work to do. [00:02:39] (Man 4) The situation is very difficult: war, death, war, fighting.', 'Afghanistan;Alienation;Class;Community;Culture;Education;Family;France;Iraq;Language;Netherlands;Pakistan;Politics;War', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1durHmE111XcDvQJagmhT2WBY8nQzNHl4CHPTX0rLbZA/edit', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1p3DNUl5s2bptOtGW14fWqCYuzY44y5Ok/view', 'Yasmeen', NULL, 0, 0),
(32, '32', 'Ahmed (1)', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Refugee/Asylum', NULL, NULL, 'Iraq;Kurdistan;Syria', 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] I was a student at that time. When the war started in Syria I graduated.\n[00:00:07] By that time I had to leave and I moved to the Kurdistan region of Iraq and I worked as a Communication for Development Consultant for the UN, working for the Syrian refugees and Iraqi displaced people.\n[00:00:19] It was a very difficult and hard decision to make to leave your home because I had my family there, you know, they told me ‘you need to move out’, because I was wanted to serve in the military, the Syrian regime of/in the military\n[00:00:38] and if I go and serve in the military I would have two options: either to kill people or people are going to kill me. So the two better options. And the only option which I had on the other side was to leave the country to things settle down.\n[00:00:54] So I thought I might leave for one, two weeks maybe a month to things settle down. Now it’s three years.', 'Alienation;Education;Family;Iraq;Kurdistan;Syria;War', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1yC-DQ51Z5N29nxZ3TR3ceysaYB6LDJEx43CVhwAv7og/edit?usp=sharing', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1qtSKAaqR3DvV71TkyJpWKsULmVdrDyp9/view?usp=sharing', 'Francesca', NULL, 0, 0),
(33, '33', 'Ahmed (2)', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Refugee/Asylum', NULL, NULL, 'Syria', 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] It was a very difficult decision to make because it’s your mother, it’s your brother, your sisters, it’s family, you know, your wife, at that time I didn’t have a child yet.\n[00:00:10] so it was literally after I got married, after one week, I had to leave because of the bombing in my place.\n[00:00:20] It was a horrendous journey, an appalling journey from the first step to the last step until I got here in the UK, to involve human traffickers, smugglers, fake IDs, crossing borders, crossing gravers, crossing seas, flying over countries, putting yourself in the back of lorries and refrigerator trucks. A lot of horrible nasty stuff.', 'Alienation;Family;Syria;War;Wellbeing', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1LTzJsmJMuTiN54CdpN7jm2KTISgTvYg4S41Vm91DiLM/edit?usp=sharing', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1y4YCqAN41PkN2yy2LhE44qu_3hlTPma6/view?usp=sharing', 'Francesca', NULL, 0, 0),
(34, '34', 'Ahmed (3)', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Refugee/Asylum', NULL, NULL, 'Syria', 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] It’s a very sophisticated and well-organised group of people who run this networks of smuggling, you know, human trafficking and so, they got their brokers on the ground [00:00:13] and they are very active on social media. So you look up for them on Facebook or Twitter, you can find them, or their names, their emails, their mobile phones and you contact them and you choose the one that suits you best. [00:00:25] It’s an open market you know, it’s the black market so [00:00:29] it depends like, the irony was I met a smuggler. It was me and another Iraqi person. So he asked the Iraqi guy to give him like five thousand dollars. But he asked me for three thousands because he said ‘look, your country is at war, it’s very difficult, so we have a discount because you are Syrian’.', 'Alienation;Family;Iraq;Syria;War', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/16QVT-5rv8b9MVFQaXApgAeQ4pMnTX_1tfJSjvxJ4ELU/edit?usp=sharing', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/17jGOTjC5bm4HH0jiEHsz-ogmysrlDvIO/view?usp=sharing', 'Francesca', NULL, 0, 0),
(35, '35', 'Ahmed (4)', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Refugee/Asylum', 'Education', NULL, 'Syria', 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] I got long term plans and short term plans. [00:00:04] The short term plan is to find a proper work, to help myself and support my family. [00:00:10] And the long term plan is to have my Master’s in Post Conflict development because I’m hoping to get, they allow a lot of scholarships available for Syrians so I am trying to get one of them, so I can continue my education and masters in Post Conflict Development so hopefully one day after the war is over we can go back to Syria and be part of their rebuilding process.', 'Education;Family;Pride;Syria;War', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1jIBB_64ofHABecpxi-FfUZyj0FEHvWmWj4XGKQTBxcU/edit?usp=sharing', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1H2xRj_YsOmRvnA7A2kaE8R-InzE6oz-3/view', 'Jess', NULL, 0, 0),
(36, '36', 'Ahmed (5)', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Refugee/Asylum', 'Economic', NULL, 'Syria', 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] I’m very happy to have my portrait painted by by Hannah because, like coming from the Middle East you know its always this is kind of the upper class thing. If you have money, if you have the you know the power. So you’ve got someone commission someone to come and paint you. I mean you know to to you pay them to portray or to paint you. [00:00:27] for me it was totally different I’m coming from a normal background someone invited me said look why don’t you come and I’ll I’ll paint you. I said yeah of course but I’ve got nothing they said no its not about having anything or not its about having you which I am very delighted. [00:00:43] I think if I got 100 thousand people listening to my story and one of them I I succeed and the the portrait succeed in changing one person’s attitude it’s a great achievement. And that’s it.', 'Class;Culture;Pride;Syria', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1r2VJBxeKHU3bfeBFH_LRuWyW6-xplVkXI42VA5s6IEs/edit?usp=sharing', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1fvgGFdLLrxPfbMlXoSa_ymVnFSiFCDFT/view', 'Jess', NULL, 0, 0),
(37, '37', 'Annie Gavrilescu (1)', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Refugee/Asylum', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[00:00: 01] The census is absolutely vital. [00: 00: 03] When we first did it before the eviction the main purpose for it was to counter the official estimate of the population the official numbers were eight hundred to one thousand people in the South which were in danger of getting evicted. [00:00:15] Our census found three thousand four hundred and fifty five people in the South who were going to be evicted. [00:00: 23] So proving the numbers and proving that a methodology, the methodology that we had was infinitely more accurate than the official one and was a really really big part of the court case.', 'Healthcare;Politics', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1N_lLyZvUE3vOJQ7KSg4yHWpjRDCGLexyxKfIk1XYMWA/edit?usp=sharing', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/145ehzwHrAnmROoHidqhlboVXfHP2qe-0/view', 'Jess', NULL, 0, 0),
(38, '38', 'Annie Gavrilescu (2)', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Refugee/Asylum', 'Child Migration', NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:00] Every single month now we will be doing a follow-up census.The reason we’re continuing with this work is to have a longitudinal study of the population in the camp. So, we will see patterns of population movement, we will see more new arrivals coming, and we can use that to make predictions for the summer once the weather gets better, and we’re expecting many more people. [00:00:23] We’re also trying to track unaccompanied children, so that we know the accurate numbers and we pass on those details to Citizens UK who are working on family reunification under the Dublin 3 Convention for the unaccompanied children and adults as well.\n[00:00:40] We’re also trying to find more detailed information about the kind of vulnerabilities that people have, and that information will go back to the L’auberge and Help Refugees team and they will be using that to try and address those special needs that people may have.', 'Family;Healthcare;Politics;Republic of Ireland;Wellbeing', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/18vYNelvFLdV3Spc62CUlS910qHyUfs1ti_LEdUdy50M/edit?usp=sharing', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1IHI9EyIV-_8p2GNalnK-4u2TBPTiIj_D/view?usp=sharing', 'Celia', NULL, 0, 0),
(39, '39', 'Annie Gavrilescu (3)', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Refugee/Asylum', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:00] In terms of successes.. Officially, not many. The authorities still tend to win over us, the eviction still happened. There was a great deal of upheaval, there was a lot of violence, people lost their homes. We found that 470 households were displaced during the eviction: either destroyed or ones that we managed to move. Not many, but we did move some. [00:00:20] So, one really important thing for us is to have accurate data. That allows us to, you know, any arguments that we make have a lot more weight when we have accurate and important data, and it will be useful for a long time to come.', 'Politics;Third person', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1d6gQwJPwUbyrcL6utlSFPEkwc6GzIotelZ9iOqcWtII/edit?usp=sharing', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1FXGd_xvd--CQ01Fq59N-xw5klpgdKni_/view?usp=sharing', 'Celia', NULL, 0, 0),
(41, '40 (a)', 'Azzat (1)', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Refugee/Asylum', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:00] It is not was been my decision to become community leader. Since we arrive in Jungle of Calais, there was been real, a very, very miserable situation for the people over there. [00:00:13] Every nation they was being scared for other nation. When we was being sleeping, we was expected maybe, afghanis are gonna attack us or kurdish are gonna attack us or some kind like that.\n[00:00:27] I was thinking to make something more positive in that place, to do something to make people more harmony, and more closer, be more friendly. It is start by a little group, their name Refugee Voice, we start this. [00:00:45] Me and, I had Afghani, and Egyptian, and Kurdish. We was been sitting on the Afghani’s shop drinking tea, and I was tell them about to make like this, six, little bit. To let people see we are friends, and they can do same, what we are doing.', 'Afghanistan;Alienation;Community;Egypt;Ethnicity;France;Friends;Kurdistan;War;Wellbeing', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1gFX_3qu_Uy9BJc5YtWeZMrUWGvDZDSe3/edit?usp=sharing&ouid=114716866458378633429&rtpof=true&sd=true', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1e5h3wfB-IDVvsuCYH-f9BRIwVtbM0-j7/view?usp=sharing', 'Kaytie', NULL, 0, 0),
(42, '41', 'Azzat (2)', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Refugee/Asylum', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:00] One day I start to have a, like a hundred metre distance. They ask, the governor (?), he want me to. We was been looking to meet this governor for a long time because we want to make more safety for the people inside the camp. We want to talk about the police violence. \n\n[00:00:18]\nAnd unfortunately when he come, the (?), he didn’t say anything about this even when I ask him about, okay, what do you think about the police violence against refugees? He say, if he were me, to stop this violence, accept it to have a hundred metres distance from highway road. \n\n[00:00:38]\nI want to keep the people safe. I said okay we’re gonna accept this, but, you already said you will gonna stop police violence. I go around and I talk to the people. \n\n[00:00:54]\nThe good thing is people they was being very trust me. If any problem between two nation they find me on the middle to kind of like slow this problem between these two nation and to make things very clean (?). All of them they respect me so much. \n\n[00:01:08]\nBecause of that I was been, okay say, okay we will gonna do that. Even other community leaders they will been refuse these things. Said to them, no. We should accept it because we want to be in safe place. We don’t want fight. And we are not here to fight at all.', 'Alienation;Community;France;Politics;War;Wellbeing', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1ntmDEzrBQUZ67hYPbvg8sdsOh09-iCV9/edit?usp=sharing&ouid=114716866458378633429&rtpof=true&sd=true', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1uclO0FWINlijy9MFP-ZKAJXSXcMjzZFp/view?usp=sharing', 'Kaytie', NULL, 0, 0),
(43, '42', 'David Cameron (1)', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Refugee/Asylum', 'Forced Migration/Enslavement', NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[0:00] Now, the shadow chancellor is pointing, the shadow chancellor... The idea that those two right honourable gentlemen would stand up to anyone in this regard is laughable. Look at the record over the last week. They’ve met with the unions, and they gave them flying pickets. They met with the Argentinians, they gave them the Falkland island. They met with a bunch of migrants in Calais, and they said they could all come to Britain. The only people they never stand up for are the British people and the hard-working taxpayers.', 'Argentina;Politics', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/14l7q-l8nJ30ZoAENszOOSdSuwEEX0hFP/edit?usp=sharing&ouid=114716866458378633429&rtpof=true&sd=true', 'https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1FRqDp0jTOpYSii1HCRDdA0nVo_64R-74', 'Mariri', NULL, 0, 0),
(44, '43', 'David Cameron (2)', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Refugee/Asylum', 'Child Migration', NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[0:00] The NCA, the National Crime Agency, one of its core tasks is to challenge, to break up and to take to court organized gangs of criminals whether they are trafficking children, or whether they are trafficking migrants. [0:13] Look, this is very testing. I accept that because you got a swarm of people coming across the Mediterranean, seeking a better life, wanting to come to Britain. Because Britain’s got jobs, it’s got a growing economy, it’s an incredible place to live. But we need to protect our borders by working hand in glove with our neighbours, the French, and that’s exactly what we are doing.', 'Community;France;Politics', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1TtswLGidwZnixjEqTKq1Nw888flhsgKp/edit?usp=sharing&ouid=114716866458378633429&rtpof=true&sd=true', 'https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1FRqDp0jTOpYSii1HCRDdA0nVo_64R-74', 'Mariri', NULL, 0, 0),
(45, '44', 'David Cameron (3)', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', NULL, 'Refugee/Asylum', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:00]This is absolutely tragic and dreadful news. And my thoughts are with Joes husband Brandon, and the two children that’s a wider a family [00:00:008]. We’ve lost a great star. She was a MP, great campaigning MP with huge compassion, with a big heart and people are gona’ be very [00:00:20] very sad, what is happened. Dreadful. Dreadful news. It’s right that we are suspending campaigning activity in this referendum and everyone thoughts will be with Joes family [00:00:30] with her constituents at this terrible time. She was a very strong campaigning MP. She had a great track record of caring about refugees. [00:00:40] And she had taken a very big interest in how we could look after Syrian refugees and the right things to do in our world. She has a huge heart. She was a very compassionated campaigning MP[00:00:50]. She was a bright star. From what I know about it, a bright star for her constituency, a star in Parliament and a star road across house. We’ve lost a star. But a bavile [00:01:00] thinking about her husband Brandon, the children, a family and her constituents. They will be feeling this huge sense of lost tonight. [00:01:10] And I think it’s right we stopped the campaigning activity. We’ve think of them. And think of what they’ve lost.', 'Family;Politics;Syria', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1GmbwXzLXn1ru1ti_zk0CBTNDp0wp0lx7MeklEU7TMlQ/edit?usp=sharing', 'https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1FRqDp0jTOpYSii1HCRDdA0nVo_64R-74', 'Marie-Aude', NULL, 0, 0),
(46, '45', 'George Clooney', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', NULL, 'Refugee/Asylum', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:000] 24 hours news doesn’t mean you get more news, just means you get the same news more. So that, more and more and more you hear, you know… These guys, the radio is go up because they show up empty (p)audience [00:00:10] say Donald Trump is about to speak. You know. As opposed to taking those thirsty seconds and say what is talk about refugees? Which is the biggest crisis going on in the world right now[00:00:20]. Hm, you know, we’d really hoard [00:00:22]the corporation far on their knees, if we did actually inform a little bit. One of the things I think… It is a great… a disaster [00:00:30] in the way we inform ourselves right now. Which is… We’ve lost the ability to, to get to until the true thing into the fact.', 'Politics;TV', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1lbk4C387j0UjVflrhS0hQABZ0YN-bZ0bYcdrMUA_JvU/edit?usp=sharing', 'https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1FRqDp0jTOpYSii1HCRDdA0nVo_64R-74', 'Marie-Aude', NULL, 0, 0),
(47, '46', 'Jeremy Corbyn', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', NULL, 'Forced Migration/Enslavement', 'Refugee/Asylum', NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[00:00] The whole of the labour family is devistered tonight.\n[00:03] Joe cox has been killed, doing her duty, doing her work, as a constituency mp\n[00:10] She is somebody who dedicated her life to human right and justice\n[00:14] She worked for antislavery campaigns, she worked for oxfam, and she became an mp for the place she grow up in and loved\n[00:24] In parliament she was respected across the whole house, someone with a deep commitment and deep passion for human right and justice\n[00:33] Sadily, today, she died. She was killed, on the streets, on her constituency doing her duty, as a local member of parliament- helping people.\n[00:45] She leaves behind a husband, a wonderful man, who likewise spends his time campaigning for human rights and justice. And she leaves behind two young children. Two young children who will never grow up to see their mum again.\n[1:03] They can be proud of what she was, they can be proud of what she did, and they can be very proud of everything she stood for.\n[1:13] We come together at a time like this, we come together to support the family and to mourn, and reflect, that violence is not an answer, violence is not an answer to anything\n[1:25] We need to come together and express our deepest condolences to Joe and her family. [1:32] We lost a wonderful wonder we lost a wonderful member of parliament\n[1:26] But our democracy will go on, her work will go on, as we mourn her memory, we will work in her memory to achieve that better world she spent her life trying to achieve.', 'United Kingdom;Family;Politics', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1EucNfjyRkZ2rmt_ouWzuX5eCFd0FWwGleSbjJOrMyZM/edit?usp=sharing', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1uuI0X2L19RdUl8zhXg1iCPFc1RJ5M89z/view?usp=sharing', 'David. W', NULL, 0, 0),
(49, '48', 'Jeremy Corbyn', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Refugee/Asylum', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] This […..] programme spoke of humanitarian challenges. We are grateful to Lord Dubs to taking on the challenge of making the governments more humanitarian. [00:00:12] Just a few weeks previously, Mr Speaker, this Prime Minister when referring to refugees fleeing persecution as a bunch of migrants and a swom. [00:00:22] I have to say this, those words were wrong, I hope the Prime Minister will think again about them and recognise, as everyone should, that refugees are simply human beings just like any of us in this chamber who are trying to survive in a very dangerous and very cruel world. [00:00:40] We need to solve their problems with humanity not with that kind of language.', 'Alienation;Language;Politics;Wellbeing', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1foskfKb13lZubxihgBQDSTgIKiNUG-ub/edit?usp=sharing&ouid=114716866458378633429&rtpof=true&sd=true', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/11UO4GdNClw1sVaa0EAZjxRVOgmq7cbWU/view?usp=sharing', 'GT', NULL, 0, 0),
(50, '49', 'Danielle Lawrence', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', NULL, 'Refugee/Asylum', NULL, NULL, 'Syria', 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] I met a fifteen year old boy. We got talking and I said ‘what’s your story?’ and he said ‘I came over from Syria, my parents sent me with smugglers, they paid smugglers’. [00:00:14] ‘And on the boat, it started to sink and they started to throwing off the boat every single boy that was on their own, every boy that was single.\nAnd he was fifteen and he put his arm into the boy, link to the boy next to him, and said secretly ‘we are brothers, we are brothers, they won’t throw us off’. And he succeeded to stay on that boat. They got to let […] . He wasn’t thrown off. The others drowned. And he made his way to Kaleh he was on his own. [00:00:46] And I said ‘please tell what can I bring you? Anything you want from England. What can I bring you?’. And he cried and looked me in the eyes and said ‘please just bring me my mom, I just want my mother’. [00:01:01] My eldest child is fourteen and it could have been her.', 'England;Family;Syria;Wellbeing', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/164XRrqI4jJ1CYYWK1rVVzZrotneVNmqli3H-yGmAd1s/edit?usp=sharing', 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1h79CLbA4hml7NvGlePFe5vK9wCCtBAmV/view?usp=sharing', 'Francesca', NULL, 0, 0);
