(266, '264', 'Jo Cox', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Emigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Syria', 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '(00:00:01) Thank you Mr speaker, I have to say once again that it is a shame that the security state an not be here personally for an important discussion on this matter, I hope this will be noted\n(00:00:14) On current trends without international action, at this end of this short debate another two Syrian citizens will be dead and four will be badly injured. \n(00:00:24) On Friday, desperate doctors in Aleppo appeal for international help to save our further massacres and the potential besiegement of that city fearing a repeat of the horrors in strebaneezer. \n(00:00:37) In light of this, does the minister agree that it is the Syrian authorities who are primary responsible for these horrific on-going abusive continuing their long standing policy of targeting civilians in rebel held areas. \n(00:00:54) Does the Prime minster now agree that urgently now need a mechanism with clear consequences to deter further barbaric attacks on civilians, I have raised repeatedly in this place the need for a no bombing zone, will he look at it now. \n(00:01:12) What is the UK also doing to work with all those with an influence over parties to this conflict including Saudi Arabia, Turkey, Iran and Russia to put pressure on all sides to stop all attacks on civilian targets, including hospitals. \n(00:01:28) And does the minister have evidence that Russian forces have been directly involved in the latest airstrikes and if they were does he not agree that it is surely time to look at fresh sanctions against Russia. \n(00:01:42) Isn’t also now time for his department along with the ministry of defense and defib to look again at air drops to besieged communities, why can we now not join the forces of European allies to get food to starving people, and wouldn’t the act of airdrops put regime on new pressure and more traditional and reliable land access. \n(00:02:05) and on accountability, is his department involved in the collection of evidence to enable war crime trials as we did during the Folkins conflict, I understand that commission of justice and accountability which is funded both by the UK and the US governments, has evidence to link abusers to the highest level of the Syrian state. \n(00:02:25) On refugees giving the escalation of the violence in Aleppo on the lack of medical care that is available now, what further can they do to let the most vulnerable people out of harm\'s way and surely, given what we know about the horror that many of the refugee’s children in Europe have fled isn’t time to end the government shameful refusal to give three thousand unaccompanied children sanctuary here in the UK. \n(00:02:50) And finally Mr speaker whilst I am a huge fan of President Obama and indeed worked for him in North Carolina in 2008 \n(00:03:01) on Syria, I believe that both President Obama and the Prime minster made the biggest misjudgment of all time in office, when they put Syria on the too difficult pile and instead of engaging fully, withdraw and out their faith in the policy of containment, this judgement made by both leaders for different reasons will I believe be judged harshly by history and has been nothing short of a foreign policy disaster, but there is still time for both men to write a post striped to this failure, so does the minster agree it is time for the leaders of both our counties even in mix of two hotly contested campaigns to launch a bold initiative to protect civilians to get aid to besieged communities and to throw our collective weight behind the fragile piece talks before they fail. \n(00:03:50) I don’t believe that even President Obama or the prime minster tried to do harm in Syria, but as is said Mr speaker sometimes all it takes for evil to triumph is for good men to nothing.', 'Politics;Syria;Thrid Person;Wellbeing', '', NULL, NULL, 'Sydney', NULL, 0, 0),
(267, '265', 'Karen Moynihan', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Afghanistan;Eritrea;Sudan;Syria', 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '(00:00:01) My name is Karen Moynihan im from Dublin in Ireland and I work as part of the team in refugee youth service \n(00:00:07) our main target group is our unaccompanied minors who are living and are arriving in the Calais camp, setting up a safe space for young people, which is just for young people to allow them to interact with their peers and the group and just let them be a young person and the camp we support young people getting shelter we have education provision and food everyday and we general support, a lot of it can be with medical or illegal services as well and obviously we don’t offer that ourself we connect them the correct services and then follow up with them as well. \n(00:00:40) nearly everyone we work with are boys and their aged generally from twelve from about eighteen years and there from a variety of different countries around the world, Afghanistan, Syria, Eritrea, Sudan and a huge amount of them are unaccompanied, they’ve travelled long long distances by themselves and suppose when they have reached here they make such an unbelievable amazing journey considering their age and even what they had with them, whether it was such a lack of money and clothing, food and I think a lot of young people believe when they get here the last step will be quite simple and unfortunately it is not. \n(00:00:40) nearly everyone we work with are boys and their aged generally from twelve from about eighteen years and there from a variety of different countries around the world, Afghanistan, Syria, Eritrea, Sudan and a huge amount of them are unaccompanied, they’ve travelled long long distances by themselves and suppose when they have reached here they make such an unbelievable amazing journey considering their age and even what they had with them, whether it was such a lack of money and clothing, food and I think a lot of young people believe when they get here the last step will be quite simple and unfortunately it is not. ', 'Afghanistan;Education;Eritrea;Sudan;Syria;Third Person', '', NULL, NULL, 'Sydney', NULL, 0, 0),
(268, '266', 'Karen Moynihan', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Afghanistan;Eritrea;Sudan;Syria', 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '(00:00:00) There teenage boys, they like nice clothes and they like to hang out with there friends and they want a particular type of phone an they like things which other teenage boys in Europe like, but unforgettably the other side of that is they had to step into a adult world very very quickly and quite a ferocious adult world they’re living in a refugee in North France with very little provision and little support for them and they have to make decision which affects their lives on a day to day basis, so I see them go on a high and low and very depressed. \n(00:00:37) What adds on that at the moment as well is that since the southern part of unofficial camp has been demolished we as a service see young people trying so much more to get to the UK illegally, like putting their lives at risk every night, they’re not getting enough sleep, they’re not getting enough food and they’re absolutely exhausted and is absolutely horrible to have to watch, have one more dream completely crushed, making them feel like there irrelevant and not important when it should be the exact opposite. ', 'Afghanistan;Education;Eritrea;Sudan;Syria;Third Person', '', NULL, NULL, 'Sydney', NULL, 0, 0),
(269, '267', 'Kent School Children', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '(00:00:00) I feel sympathy for them, as they have been in though these situation and the camp dwellers have had to flee from their homeland due to other war dictatorship and things like that.  \n(00:00:12) On the other hand, I also feel that they kind put themselves in that situation as they really haven’t tried to seek asylum other countries they have just coming over to England really and haven’t put enough effort in to try to stay in another country, either by learning another language or a job. \n(00:00:34) I think some of the people in the camp might of faced like because their countries might of faced war or different things that they could of come through like they could of lost family members or houses, homes and different personal belongings. \n(00:00:52) My message would be to try and explain to them to maybe stay in France or another country that they’ve already been through because our country getting full already and there is enough people with different problems and it would be hard to help them aswell. ', 'Education;Thrid Person', '', NULL, NULL, 'Sydney', NULL, 0, 0),
(270, '268', 'Kes', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '(00:00:00) Afghanistan to Pakistan, Pakistan to Iran, Iran to Turkey, Turkey to Bulgaria, Bulgaria to Servia, Servia come to Austria, Austria come to Germany, Germany come to Holland, Belgium then Belgium come here.\n(00:00:20) sometimes by car sometimes by walking more of the walking and some of car I think 15 or 14 people inside. ', 'Afghanistan;Berlin;Bulgaria;Germany;Holland;Iran:Pakistan;Turkey;', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(271, '269', 'Lorry Driver 1', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '(00:00:00) They have not got any fear whatsoever of the place, cause they know if they catch them, they’ll send them back to try another day, or try in a couple of hours.(00:00:10) There is a big long snake of them coming up the motorway, just 2 or 3 hundred coming of the train trying to get through the fencing, so I got a funny feeling we could get stuck, so we’ll see.   ', 'Thrid Person', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(272, '270', 'Lorry Driver 2', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '(00:00:01) You have to be very careful where you park with security, theres no parking in laybys, you got to be weary when you have to sleep at night in the truck for any movement in the truck seeing if anyone is trying to get in or trying to steal the diesel.(00:00:18) The drivers are bearing the work load when they have to, noone goes to work 10-15 hours a day and expect a £2,000 fine at the end of it, its more and more put under the driver, this is going on everyday of every week of the year and has gone on for the past few years it seems, God forbid none of the drivers will get injured since it is on the card and might happen.', 'Thrid Person', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(273, '271', 'Lorry Driver 3', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '(00:00:00) there always been a problem with immigrants but in the past 2 or 3 years its gotten worse. \n\n(00:00:09) When I first started to go abroad there was the immigrants, but they was no where near as ruthless as they are now, not as desperate as you like. Your biggest worry is trying to park at Calais at night, you had to avoid that because they trying to sneak in while you\'re asleep, now in the last 2 years certainly definitely, it\'s like they changed from middle eastern to African descendants and they are just more ruthless, they try it every day and in broad daylight, working together where before it was 2 or 3 but now it\'s like a group of 30, it’s becoming a massive problem. ', 'Thrid Person', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(274, '272', 'Lorry Driver 4', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '(00:00:00) It’s scary to tell the change and know that we shouldn’t have to be parked up at the side of the road with people throwing stones, bars and sticks and getting gassed. \n(00:00:11) Its not one or two it’s a gang, you can get out your cab with one or two not twenty-two \n(00:00:18) You know it becomes intimidating, you don’t want to get out, you just want to phone the police, but you know how long it takes for them to come out to you. \n(00:00:25) Everyone must be scared and that’s why, you know you got to plan your route now, drivers use to help each other now you can’t, you sit in your cab and be quite otherwise you get stoned, you get bricked, you get cut. \n(00:00:36) Yeah, I\'ve been gassed before, I went for some food and got gassed cause you try and help these people with the break in and you try help, so you get gassed =, just an everyday thing, it’s a scary thing out there. ', 'Thrid Person', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(275, '273', 'Lorry Driver 5', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '(00:00:00) I don’t know when its gonna end, I don’t have the answers for that, but it is a scary time at the moment. \n(00:00:06) something has to be done, how desprate are they to kill somebody to get over there cause that’s the only thing that will happen, you know things will change when it happens. \n(00:00:19) Noone wants to know about throwing rocks the people being cut the window screens getting smashed, the curtains getting sliced, you know noone wants to about this, it will only happen when somebody dies, \n(00:00:34) and that’s when we’ll take action, to stop it ', 'Thrid Person', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(276, '274', 'Waseem', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Syria', 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '(00:00:00) I’m Waseem from Syria 36 years old \n(00:00:05) Actually there is two ways to get to, across to the UK, first one by the ferry, we walk through jungle through the night to the ferry trying to hide inside the truck or we can go to the train station and try to jump on the train when start to move. \n(00:00:35) We use to go there daily for three months we walked to the train station. \n(00:00:41) At 28km we spend the at least seven hours walking, waiting, hiding. \n(00:00:51) We didn’t make it because it has become impossible. \n(00:01:01) Whatever it takes we should walk we should drive, so we don’t care about if its cold, if its rainy. We didn’t think it would be like this. \n(00:01:16) It’s horrible. ', 'alienation;wellbeing', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(277, '275', 'Lucy Wilson', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '(00:00:00) My name is Lucy Clark Wilson, when I go to the Calais camp, we’re working with an organization called HOWER that stands for humanitarian, Aid and Well-being association.  \n(00:00:11) The intention of the project is to work with people in the camp refugees and volunteers with the idea that we can involve people as much as possible in making choices about what type of support they want, so that might be around fundraising to help build the Mosk might be around direct aid which we often do through care for Calais as well, an organisation that has been working long-term there with Clare Mosely. \n(00:00:39) Or might be doing some well-being projects, such as the art work being displayed at the Migration Museum often with unaccompanied minors, with adults and with the children in the camp. \n(00:00:40) Last trip that we went we sat alongside the football pitch where there had been over 100 men playing football on one sunny day afternoon and we’d lay out some blankets, took some sweets and hang out there with lots of the art materials and the men crowed around to see in interest what was going on, in a lot of them they talked about the joy that it gave them having a moment just to transcend into the art work. ', 'France; Thrid Person', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(278, '276', 'Mahmoud', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Syria', 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '(00:00:00) My name is Mahmoud, I am from Syria I am here for 5 months  \n(00:00:07) I can’t be allowed here, I will stay here it’s an incredible life, use to wake up in the morning try to find something to do, try to help anything making fire to take a shower. \n(00:0034) When we go to town we have to wait 2 hours to take 6 minutes shower, in the cold, its snowy, and it doesn’t matter, sometimes we’ll be sick because of this shower and sometimes we go out of this and its snowy, its windy, its very cold so when we have showers we have an active 6 minutes with 2hours waiting. Its terrible ', 'Culture;Syria;Wellbeing', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(279, '277', 'Maya Conforti', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Refugee/Asylum', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '(00:00:00) My name is Mya Conforti I am a member of ------ which is a local NGO that has been working with the refugee since 2008 and on this jungle since beginning which is April 2015 \n(00:00:17) It began with absolutely nothing the refugee that lived in Calais and 7 or 8 different smaller jungles were told by the government to move here, they was forced by the government and so they moved to a piece of virgin land which actually was not quite virgin in the sense that it was a form of dumb of constructions materials so look pretty awful and its 35 acres large, so its quite big, but when you moved here there was absolutely nothing, no road, no light, no water points, no toilets, nothing. ', 'Thrid Person', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(280, '278', 'Maya Conforti', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CMBMN', NULL, NULL, '(00:00:00) it has become a town, kinda a small town because, the living conditions are still difficult, you know there\'s mud everywhere, it\'s cold there\'s no heat. However, it is a town in the fact that it has services, it has a church, it has serval Mosks, it has 2 schools, it has a library, a woman centre, a youth centre, a police centers, several communities\' kitchens which serve 100 of meals everyday, it has points where people can get clothing and shoes and so on and many restaurants and shops ', 'Thrid Person', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
