(2826, '2819', 'Carol Ann Uszkura, artofcarol@aol.com', 'artofcarol@aol.com', '1960s', 'Image', 'Immigration', 'Forced Migration/Enslavement', 'No details', 'No details', 'Poland', 'Disc', 'At least one of my parents migrated here', NULL, 'My dad came here with the Polish Army at the end of World War II. He was qualified in metallurgy but the UK would not accept this as he was taught in the metric system, so he could only get unskilled labour work. In 1960 an enlightened employer took him on as a scaffolding safety inspector, a job he thrived in and did for the rest of his working life as it used his knowledge of metals. He was never able to return home. His only sibling, a brother, wrote to him from behind the Iron Curtain in the late forties to say it was unsafer for them communicate. This leaves me with unknown family over there. My father had a huge disregard for nationalism which I have inherited. Ban borders, let us, as John Lennon said, ‘all live as one’.', 'Family;Poland;War;Commerce;Alienation;Education;Politics;War;Ethnicity', '', '', NULL, NULL, '', 1, 0),
