(10009, '10001', 'Chris Mak', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Child Migration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TCOB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] CM: A lot of times it was come back from school and do your homework and then\nyeah, just like whenever it gets busy err the door was open and then my mum was like “洗個\n菠菜 [wash some vegetables],” like “菠菜 [some vegetables].” And then like, you know, slam\nthe door.\n[00:00:14] CM: And then I’d have to run down. So that was quite annoying. You’re just\nconstantly want to do other stuff before you’ve been told to come down, come down, come\ndown. You don’t really have much of a personal life. You couldn’t exactly go out after school,\nto go out and hang out with friends, or whatever. Even on weekends, you’ve got to go back\nby 4:30[pm] to start to prepare for helping out with the shop and everything.\n[00:00:38] CM: So it always come up as my least favourite memory is not really having much\nof a childhood so to speak. But I am grateful for it because I now know how to cook. I know\nthe - the value of money.\n[00:00:54] CM: I know hard work. I’ve seen hard work - what it translates to because in the\nbusiness like this there is literally no days off. If you take a day off, then you’re not going to\nmake any money. Then you come to realise fairly quickly that all of the efforts literally goes\ntowards your livelihood.\n[00:01:11] CM: So um yeah, I realised that fairly early on over the years of doing more of\nthis. So um, yeah, not taking for granted what work goes into until I’ve made money basically\nso [...]\n[00:01:21] INTERVIEWER: Yeah. Do you work anywhere else?\n[00:01:24] CM: I was working as a marketer for Formula 1 doing all of their marketing\ncampaigns and things. That was very, very hands-on. Very high up[??] so a lot of work\ninvolved in that.\n[00:01:37] CM:And I guess having being in that takeaway industry, I guess you could say,\nbeing in that warzone definitely helped with this work ethic. The work ethic, motivation\nelsewhere just like head-down, keep pushing on - that kind of thing.\n[00:01:53] CM: This is I guess something I kinda help out with now and then when I’m back\nin town. Because business isn’t as busy nowadays, I don’t come to help out as much.\n[00:02:03] CM: But whenever I go back and I’m there for dinner and it does get busy or the\nphone’s ringing, I would say - voluntarily go up and just say “炒飯 [fried rice]” here and there\nand that’s that.\n[00:02:14] CM: So, rather just sit there and let my parents just do it.\n[00:02:18] INTERVIEWER: And ??? do you think your parents will retire one day, do you\nhave anyone to take over the business or do you think that it will kinda die with them?\n[00:02:26] CM: My dad has said that he plans to retire in two years. So [...] Ok, now dad is\nmaybe saying “What should we do with the shop?” No-one is going to take it over. We could\neither lease it out, we could sell the building, we could turn it into an accomodation.\n[00:02:44] CM: He has said many times that if you don’t have a job - if you end up doing\nnothing, you can fall back on um working at this takeaway. And I say “Errr [...] no thanks. But\nerr [...] thanks, but no thanks”\n\n[00:02:58] INTERVIEWER: [Laughs]. It’s nice to have that safety net.', 'Childhood; Commerce; Community; Culture; Family; Food', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1hlztRHw1wvgWvZtw_LOVClyg8nxV5cZrnDFpuBtFcIs/edit?usp=sharing', NULL, 'Jess Chow', NULL, 0, 0),
(10010, '10002', 'Lisa Lee', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Child Migration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TCOB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] INTERVIEWER: Pre-pandemic growing up in the takeaway, did you ever felt\npeople vandalising your shop? Or did you have annoying customers that would leave rice\nand chips everywhere? That kinda thing,\n[00:00:11] LL: Oh my God, I felt that I would get so pissed off. And my dad, my dad is a very\ngentle person by nature and he- his life philosophy was literally to just keep your head down\nand to keep the peace because you just don’t know - and I am coming to understand that I\ndon’t agree with that because that means if we were to be attacked then there is a high\nchance I would [???].\n[00:00:38] LL: So, in terms of growing up, there was one incident where I think it was just\ntomfoolery more than anything. But I remember it because I think I was just sleeping in my\ncot effectively until I was maybe three or four.\n[00:00:55] LL: But in the middle of the night, two men climbed in front of our shop and we\nwere sleeping. We were living upstairs and they broke through the window.\n[00:01:04] INTERVIEWER: In your bedroom window?\n[00:01:06] LL: In our bedroom, so yeah, so I was in [...] I obviously shared a room with my\nparents. They were in the bed, I was in my cot. And then they were so drunk. They were just\nmucking around. But obviously it was terrifying to have full-grown drunk men in your room,\nswinging on your bedroom light and you have no idea what’s going on.\n[00:01:26] LL: So my parents did call the police. I remember the police being there. And\nactually, talking about the police, I have had several experiences dealing with them and I\nhave to say I understand why the Chinese community is so [???] don’t call on them for help\nbecause they are really not that supportive.\n[00:01:43] LL: So nothing came from that as far as I know and then after we would get\ncustomers who would come in and just eat in our takeaway and leave a mess. And my dad\nwould just you know obviously, [???] just clean it up.\n[00:01:56] LL: Nothing violent comes to mind, although, the most recent incident that\nhappened. And this is the thing with hate crime, it’s really hard to say it’s because of racism.\nOur driver was outside of the takeaway and then a cyclist came and then maybe he\naccidentally knocked into the car. He got off the bike. He went after the driver. Driver’s\nobviously freaked out. Ran into the takeaway for safety and my dad and him tried to pole\ndown the doors and the man couldn’t get in because he was furious.\n[00:02:30] LL: And then the man basically smashed the glass on the door. The glass went\neverywhere and it cut my dad’s face and it misses his eye by centimeters. As soon as he\nsaw my dad bleeding he like ran away.\n[00:02:44] LL: But what if we hadn’t been a Chinese takeaway? We’d tried thinking if it was a\ndifferent business owned by different marginalised person? Or White person? So, my dad\nwas very good about it, but I wonder at the back of my mind how he actually felt about it,\nbeing much older and he’s not in his (you know) youth where he can handle something like\nthat. As well as he could have.\n[00:03:10] INTERVIEWER: I’m sorry that happened.', 'Childhood; Commerce; Community; Culture; Family; Food; Racism;', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/16u-liwoOLXnc3pNDBuqzabfs_ebFUy59qqhGypoXWCg/edit?usp=sharing', NULL, 'Jess Chow', 'Contains some text that needs verifying. Also contains Cantonese.', 0, 0),
(10011, '10003', 'Tom Tse', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Child Migration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TCOB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] INTERVIEWER: What were your thoughts and feelings at the time when you were\nkinda growing up and working in the Chinese takeaway? Were you still helping out as well\non weekends?\n[00:00:08] TT: I do help out every now and then when I go back to York to visit. In terms of\nhow I felt about it, because I was young I was probably ungrateful for it. Because I started\nhelping out in the takeaway since primary school, working on the weekends as well. That’s\nwhen all your friends do stuff on the weekend as well.\n[00:00:25] TT: Working from probably like half five to midnight, I probably saw it as “Ahh”, a\nbit jealous that my friends get to do stuff. I didn’t get to make a lot of friends during\nsecondary school for example.\n[00:00:36] TT: But at the same time I’m kinda glad I didn’t really do half the stuff that I heard\non the weekends. It also gave me like a lot of discipline, gave me a lot of practical skills later\non in life as well. For example, I’m quite surprised when I went to uni, I saw a lot of people\ndoesn’t [sic.] know how to cook. Something simple as that.\n[00:00:53] TT: But I’m very grateful for what they’ve done to, like, I was thinking about this\nthe other day how it would be like if we opened a Chinese takeaway now. Can we do it?\nThey sacrificed a lot just to give us comfortable living as well. It’s something we have to be\ngrateful for.\n[00:01:10] TT: Thinking about this the other day as well; I always ask them do they even\nenjoy what they are doing? And I am really scared of asking that because who actually\nenjoys takeaway life? [...] It’s a very difficult lifestyle.\n[00:01:24] INTERVIEWER: Yeah, takeaway life was all about survival for our parents’ era\nand you know, they sacrificed a lot for themselves so the second generation like us - that we\ncan go on to do better things that aren’t as backbreaking. And I guess what are your\nthoughts about that when you know, your parents have like sacrificed so much for you?\n[00:01:44] TT: I would hope that I can provide the same things for if I ever have kids, the\nsame experience - like this level of support. Definitely emotionally and financially.', 'Childhood; Commerce; Community; Culture; Family; Food;', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1hSknqGBD_7eBC6uz12gHwK_9pK-3ROdubmfXMa0NVaE/edit?usp=sharing', NULL, 'Jess Chow', 'Contains some text that possibly needs verifying.', 0, 0),
(10012, '10004', 'Winnie Nip', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Child Migration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TCOB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] INTERVIEWER: What were your favourite jobs to do in the takeaway?\n[00:00:05] WN: I liked stealing chips. [laughs] In between the customers, I would hang\naround in the kitchen - steal some chips. I also just liked doing nothing that was to do with\nthe takeaway so like reading the trashy magazines, watching Eastenders.\n[00:00:21] WN: But otherwise, things I did like to do is kinda a weird one so I really liked the\nprep before the shop opened. So, doing all the fried rice, putting the lids on the fried rice to\ncontainers. Only because it was very methodical and everyone had like a routine. So, go in\nthe tub, you would collect it, then you’d press the lids on and it would go in a pile.\n[00:00:47] WN: I really enjoyed that because it was very. It was- what’s the word?\n[00:00:50] INTERVIEWER: Therapeutic, I would say?\n[00:00:51] WN: There! [laughs]\n[00:00:54] INTERVIEWER: When did your parents sell the takeaway? And what were some\nof your feelings when they sold it?\n[00:01:00] WN: They sold the takeaway in 2019, so just before Covid. My dad was ready to\nsell. I think when you work in that industry it’s so hard to find other chefs to train up. And you\nput so much of your energy training people up only for people to leave.\n[00:01:15] WN: And then my dad was at the end of them owning the shop outright, manned\na lot of the chef stations so he would be head chef and he would do everything else as well.\nMy mum on the other hand, wasn’t quite ready to sell so she found it really difficult because\nit was her livelihood.\n[00:01:35] WN: You know, she’s very precious over it and still very protective over it.', 'Childhood; Commerce; Community; Culture; Family; Food;', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1lyd1ANHf4Q46r9_iiiTPTa1kqE9UVUKaI1smQaQNjOI/edit?usp=sharing', NULL, 'Jess Chow', NULL, 0, 0),
(10013, '10005', 'Oliver Khondoker', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Economic', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TCOB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:00]\nMy mum’s background is based on the service industry, she started off in the hotels, boarding houses and then she worked her way up to the restaurants.\n[00:00:10]\nAnd then my dad on the other side, he came over to this country in 1962. He got a scholarship to attend one of the universities here, however, due to his circumstances, he couldn’t afford to continue with his course.\n[00:00:25]\nHe worked from being a kitchen porter to actually having to leave his studies because he just couldn’t afford to support himself. So, he worked within the industry and worked his way up. At one point he employed my mother, in the restaurant, in Leicester square, and that’s where they got to know each other.\n[00:00:42]\nSo, my dad was a very good cook, a really good manager. And my mum was like the brains, and she could envisage where they could both take this package. They saw a little gap in the market for Irish hospitality. My mum thought well we’re going to do that. \n[00:01:00]\nThe business is a family business. I got involved when I was 6 years old to be honest because we lived above the restaurant and there was no escape. Whenever there was a short of staff, they would get the mop head and bang it on the ceiling. Which meant we will have to come down and work. \n[00:01:13]\nSo from a young age, the restaurant dining room was our living room instead of watching tv we would watch real life unfold. \n[00:01:21]\nWe had all the Irish builders; we were like a working man café. So you would get the hearts sort of Irish men coming in the evenings, you’ll get the suited and booted office workers in the morning. You kind of learned life from just sitting there having your dinner and watching life go by and you met lots of characters. \n[00:01:38]\nIt was an unusual upbringing but I think it gave us good stead in life. A lot of people just learned their life through television, we learned it through the real, watching it through the front door and what sort of people is going to come through the door. \n[00:01:52]\nMy mum would be up at half 5, she’ll be down at the café she’ll be getting everything prepped to get ready to open the door for 7. Although they would be people already peering through the door at half six waiting to see if the kettle was on. So she will always let them in and she’ll work the whole way through serving front of house.  \n[00:02:11]\nSo her day would be filled with either be sitting down talking to customers. She liked a good smoke so in between having smoke breaks where she’ll be sitting outside with them and then another customer will pass and then she will end up talking to them for another half an hour. \n[00:02:25]\nShe loved people, she was a people person. She worked 17 hours a day she wouldn’t have a rest. She would basically finish work at half nine and she’ll come up and she’ll basically just relax and she would do it all over again 6 days a week. \n[00:02:41]\nPeople were drawn to her because she had time for everyone. She made them feel welcome, she had the time to actually sit down and say how are you doing? how are you feeling? And she said she meant it genuinely and she could sit and talk to a person in a suit, or a homeless person and she could spend as much time as she had just discussing how they were. \n[00:03:03]\nEveryone found something in my mum that they needed that comfort that sort of loyalty that warmth, that generosity. It just goes to show that the amount of people that she touched emotionally and became friends with throughout the whole the social community whether you’re white, Irish, Polish, Black, Asian, across the board, I don’t think you could ever see that someone had such an impact on so many different sorts of cultures and nations and people, its just amazing to see. \n[00:03:34]\nMy mum passed away on June the 28th 2020, the reaction and the outpour of grief was overwhelming. \n[00:03:43]\nWe knew that people wanted to come and show their respects, so even to have a funeral we were limited to 30 people within the actual service, and I believe there was 15 people allowed to the grave site.\n [00:03:56]\nSo, we gave them the opportunity to line the streets of Lewisham on the day of the funeral and we basically drove the hearse the whole way down Lewisham Road where people could social distance and pay their respects and I believe there was like over a 1000 people came out to pay their respects. \n[00:04:15]\nIt was an amazing thing to see, still doesn’t feel real actually. \n', 'Class; Commerce; Comunity; Culture; Family; Food; ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Tracy Monney', NULL, 0, 0),
(10014, '10006', 'Shams Uddin', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Economic', 'Refugee/Asylum', NULL, 'Bangladesh', 'TCOB', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:00]\nMy name is Shams Uddin, I’m the owner of Monsoon Restaurant, Brick Lane. I come from Bangladesh in 10th May 1976 and straight from Heathrow airport to Brick Lane and I’m still in Brick Lane. \n[00:00:15]\nThe first experience was in a working as a cleaner, I used to clean the factory. Then I start working as a machinist, then I decided to move on, but I don’t know what to do. I don’t want to go from Brick Lane, because when I found brick Lane, it’s like another Bangladesh. \n[00:00:34]\nSuddenly I found a job. Where the dark sugar was, I was working 23 years there. That was the famous Clifton before. There’s a lot of famous people that used to come in to Clifton. Ben Kingsley, yeah he used to come. David Attenborough used to come. People used to come from the city because there is not much restaurants in the city in that time. \n[00:00:59]\nFew industry was in before, but nowadays, lost count of how many kind of cuisine around. \n[00:01:05]\nIf you want to buy fish and chips they’re going to deliver it to your house. \n[00:01:09]\nThe guy who used to come once a week before now he comes maybe once, once in a month. \n[00:01:15]\nThere is a lot of Bengali restaurants is gonna go. It’s gonna go because of the high rent and rate.\n[00:01:22]\nI think it second highest rate we pay, in the United Kingdom.\n[00:01:26]\nAnd because of the shortage of staff, the new generation doesn’t want to come in this industry. They want to do a professional job. So this is very complicated for a business to do.\n', 'Assimilation; Bangladesh; Commerce; Culture; ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Tracy Monney', NULL, 0, 0),
(10015, '10007', 'Charlie Phillips ', NULL, NULL, 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Child Migration', 'Economic', NULL, 'Jamaica', NULL, NULL, NULL, '[00:00:00]\nI’m known as Charlie Phillips yeah, but my nickname from my past restaurant was called Smokey Joe’s, Smokey is my name. \n[00:00:08]\nI was born in Kingston Jamaica, but I grew up in the hills of St Mary’s. I was about 11 when I came to England against my will, but I had to come up and join my parents. \n[00:00:22]\nIn those days, there used to be a lot of Bachelors. Different families used to cook for different people. Well, my family had what you call a Cookshop, it wasn’t licensed. She used to cook for about 15 to 20 people. They’d come round, to the house, and have a meal there. And that’s where it started, out from a basement.\n[00:00:44]\nI started traveling around Europe, and I came back in about the 70’s. And I thought let’s have a stall. So I started to sell corn on the cobs in the market and this is how I got the name Smokey Joe. Because I used to light my BBQ and smoke up the whole place.\n[00:01:03]\n I decided to try to open a shack, not a restaurant, whaddya call a diner.  \n[00:01:09]\nI got the concept, many years ago, when I spent time in Paris. There used to be a woman, used to cook during the French resistance in the last war. And everybody from the rich and poor. You could go there and eat for cinq francs, for 5 francs. \n[00:01:26]\nSo, I thought I would bring the same concept back to London and buy my things seasonally. We’d change the menu every day. We just had about 3 main dishes and that’s it, when we sold out, we close up and go home. So that was the concept of it. \n[00:01:40]\nWe give you what we got! We get you in, we get you out, and we get your money. \n[00:01:47]\nWe’d have peppered prawns, that’s prawns cooked in garlic and butter, simmered down, and you eat the lot, with the shells served with hard dough bread, it tastes similar to the Irish soda bread. We do roasted corn and we serve it with grated coconut. My star dish would be my ribs, my BBQ spareribs. \n\n[00:02:11]\nFor the weight watchers now, I’d have my breast of Chicken Virginia done with a nice, sweet pepper sauce with strips of cheese, baked. Weight watchers, it’s called Chicken Virginia, dedicated to a regular customer of mine. Who said she’s on a diet.  \n[00:02:26]\nWe’d just apologise to every customer that came in, saying sorry I had to get rid of head waiter, we haven’t got a wine waiter, we haven’t got the maître d’, we just got a blackboard menu, here’s a pen, here’s a piece of paper, write out what you want, make up your own bill, and come and pay me after. We’re not interested in 5 stars, and 4 stars, we feed hungry people. \n[00:02:50]\nSo, it became a family type of thing. \n[00:02:54]\nWhen I wanted to expand, at the time we just couldn’t get any finance. Sorry, Mr. Phillips, it won’t be the same. In fact, we thought we’d give it 2 and half years. But I lasted 11 years and 8 months, you know.\n', 'Commerce;Culture; Ethnicity; Family; Food; Jamaica; Paris', '', NULL, NULL, 'Tracy Monney', NULL, 0, 0),
(10016, '10008', 'Jin Tian Hui', NULL, '2020s', 'Video', 'Immigration', 'Economic', 'Lesuire/Retirement', NULL, 'China', 'Other', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01]: When I came to the UK, I was scared because I didn’t know English and didn’t\nknow how to travel around. We didn’t have our place so had to stay in live-in accommodation\nwith lots of other people.\n[00:00:11]: My name is Jin Tian Hui and this year I’m 61 years old. We opened a Chinese\ntakeaway in South Wales in a small village in 1988, and we closed the shop in 2018.\n[00:00:28]: The reason we moved is because our friends and family were already here. It\nwas cheaper to buy our own place and shop here. So we bought a takeaway where we can\nwork and look after the kids.\n[00:00:45]: Everyday was really busy and I felt 24 hours a day is not enough. I wake up at\n6am, I would go downstairs to the kitchen and make breakfast for the kids.\n[00:00:55]: I would also have to start some of the takeaway prep. I’d take the kids to school\nat 8:45am and at 9am I would drive to Cardiff to go to my English language class. I’d finish at\nnoon.\n[00:01:10]: Afterwards, I would meet friends to exercise together for a gym, sauna and swim\nsession. I’d head back home at 3pm to more takeaway prep work ready for the night’s\nservice.\n[00:01:22]: We would start work at 5pm and we would work until close at midnight. We would\nstart work at 5pm and we would work until close at midnight. We would have to deep clean\nthe kitchen as well and go to sleep at 2am.\n[00:01:36]: Everyday was the same and we opened 7 days a week. My spring roll doesn’t\nhave any meat and it’s all veggies. I have prepped all the spring rolls ready before opening\nand they’re already pre-rolled.\n[00:01:50]: Whenever a customer ordered them we’d fry them fresh and serve. They’re very\npopular because they’re cheap and young people love eating them. You can put whatever\nfilling you want but for my recipe I use beanspouts, onions, carrots, peas and wood ear\nmushrooms. The colours are really beautiful.\n[00:02:15]: Then prepare all the ingredients. It’s a little bit spicy with chilli powder, sugar, salt\nand msg to the filling. The next step is the spring roll wrappers. You must cover the spring\nroll wrappers with a damp tea towel otherwise it will dry out.\n[00:02:32]: Lay one square wrapper flat on the surface, add a spoonful of the filling in the\nmiddle. Next, fold the corners and roll tightly. We prep them all first before frying. I don’t\nknow English that well.\n[00:02:55]: I can listen out for some words but when I speak it doesn’t come out right and\nsome people can’t understand me. A lot of the customers that visited wanted to chat with\nme. Sometimes I can understand customers’ stories and conversations. But I struggled to\nthink of the right words to communicate back, which I regret.\n[00:03:17]: When we accidentally packed the order wrong and sometimes customers would\ncomplain. This caused a lot of stress and arguments. When we cooked a big order and if the\ncustomer didn’t like the slightest thing, they would demand a full refund.\n[00:03:40]: My favourite thing was when my children came back on weekends. We would\nwork together and chat at the same time. It was busy, but the atmosphere was lively and\nthere would be a lot of laughs in the kitchen.\n[00:04:01]: Sometimes I would walk past the old shop and I stop to look at the signage and\nthe shop. I would feel emotional and want to cry. I know the current owners of the shop that\nwe sold the takeaway to and they always invite to visit, but it’s not the same.\n\n[00:04:22]: I really like living here now. The air is great and the people are friendly. Every\ntime I go back to China to visit relatives it always feels like a holiday rather than going home.', 'Business;Family;Food;', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1rwkVUkP2GhAjuOl3LvbavyHhuOy9PW7y/edit?usp=sharing&ouid=115921659844276086486&rtpof=true&sd=true', NULL, 'Jess C.', NULL, 0, 0),
(10017, '10009', 'Anh Ming', NULL, '2020s', 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Economic', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Other', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] INTERVIEWER: How has your family’s business been since the pandemic? I know that you are cash only as well and [...] how has your business been in comparison with takeaway and delivery and everything is all mobile phones and digital now?\n\n[00:00:14] AM: We did suggest to my parents that they should get the card machine because everyone doesn’t really [...] well a lot of people don’t use cash anymore.\n\n[00:00:22] INTERVIEWER: Yes..\n\n[00:00:23] AM: But they’re still strongly against it. Well, my dad is. He’s just like “Why should I give the card company however much they take from it? Why should I give that to them? If my customers are loyal, they will bring the cash”. Alright, ok […]  So [... laughs]  \n\n[00:00:38] INTERVIEWER: My parents are the same. They were like very adamant [...] “Oh yeah” you know, “more people will come. They’ll bring the cash.”  \n\n[00:00:45] AM: Yeah, yeah, yeah. Well, you know, they just don’t want any more money taken from them.\n\n[00:00:50] INTERVIEWER: Yeah, exactly. Like I feel [...] Like I feel my parent’s generation, they don’t understand, you know, spending more money to make more money kind of thing in terms of like marketing. And you know, they don’t understand [...] oh, what like a website?\n\n[00:01:03] AM: I mean we’ve got a really basic website with as much as we could push [...] But didn’t have anyone [...]\n\n[00:01:08] INTERVIEWER: Did you have to make the website?\n\n[00:01:10] AM: Yeah. I was the one that had to [...] at least ‘cos back in the day, in the 90s and stuff ‘cos I don’t know if you did the same but they print so many menus and then they would hire you to go and post it around the neighbourhood. I don’t know if you did the same thing I did? \n\n[00:01:26] AH: Yes I did. [Laughs]\n\n[00:01:40] INTERVIEWER: Yeah and they would rally your friends and go “Oh bring your friends and I’ll make them some chicken chow mein” or something. And you’d earn like 1p per menu and you’re like “Oh my God, that’s amazing!”. So you’d go round doing loads and getting chased by dogs. \n[00:01:40] AH: Oh my God, the dog chasing. Yeah, I have PTSD from it. \n\n[00:01:46] AM: So yeah [...]\n\n[00:01:47] AH: So we had the same although I didn’t get paid for it but it was just me and my family and we would split up. My brothers are a bit older so we could drive them. So, my brothers did it by car and then me and my parents were in the other car. \n[00:01:58] AH: We would split up and just put the menu through the letterbox, but obviously we’d forgotten what ones we’ve done ‘cos our parents were like “Oh yeah, you have to leave the menus kinda half-hanging out of the letterbox so you remember what you’ve done.” And then we forgot.   \n\n[00:02:13] AM: You would have like a printed map and have like sections [...]\n\n[00:02:15] AH: Oh yeah, the whole 1999 AA Map that’s like 6 years out of date. Battered. Erm ‘cos we did delivery as well.\n\n[00:02:25]: [End of audio]\n', 'Business;Family;Food;', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1OqXDbxIm8XQwEtNKIwxXDM2lTuNm1A_yWyf_qUiBGOo/edit?usp=sharing', NULL, 'Jess C.', 'Original video is in Cantonese with English subtitles.', 0, 0),
(10018, '10010', 'Chris Mak', NULL, '2020s', 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Economic', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Other', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] CM: A lot of times it was come back from school and do your homework and then yeah, just like whenever it gets busy err the door was open and then my mum was like “洗個菠菜 [wash some vegetables],” like “菠菜 [some vegetables].” And then like, you know, slam the door.\n[00:00:14] CM: And then I’d have to run down. So that was quite annoying. You’re just constantly want to do other stuff before you’ve been told to come down, come down, come down. You don’t really have much of a personal life. You couldn’t exactly go out after school, to go out and hang out with friends, or whatever. Even on weekends, you’ve got to go back by 4:30[pm] to start to prepare for helping out with the shop and everything. \n[00:00:38] CM: So it always come up as my least favourite memory is not really having much of a childhood so to speak. But I am grateful for it because I now know how to cook. I know the - the value of money. \n[00:00:54] CM: I know hard work. I’ve seen hard work - what it translates to because in the business like this there is literally no days off. If you take a day off, then you’re not going to make any money. Then you come to realise fairly quickly that all of the efforts literally goes towards your livelihood. \n[00:01:11] CM: So um yeah, I realised that fairly early on over the years of doing more of this. So um, yeah, not taking for granted what work goes into until I’ve made money basically so [...]\n\n[00:01:21] INTERVIEWER: Yeah. Do you work anywhere else?\n\n[00:01:24] CM: I was working as a marketer for Formula 1 doing all of their marketing campaigns and things. That was very, very hands-on. Very high up[??] so a lot of work involved in that. \n[00:01:37] CM:And I guess having being in that takeaway industry, I guess you could say, being in that warzone definitely helped with this work ethic. The work ethic, motivation elsewhere just like head-down, keep pushing on - that kind of thing. \n[00:01:53] CM: This is I guess something I kinda help out with now and then when I’m back in town. Because business isn’t as busy nowadays, I don’t come to help out as much. \n[00:02:03] CM: But whenever I go back and I’m there for dinner and it does get busy or the phone’s ringing, I would say - voluntarily go up and just say “炒飯 [fried rice]” here and there and that’s that. \n[00:02:14] CM: So, rather just sit there and let my parents just do it.\n\n[00:02:18] INTERVIEWER: And ??? do you think your parents will retire one day, do you have anyone to take over the business or do you think that it will kinda die with them? \n\n[00:02:26] CM: My dad has said that he plans to retire in two years. So [...] Ok, now dad is maybe saying “What should we do with the shop?” No-one is going to take it over. We could either lease it out, we could sell the building, we could turn it into an accomodation. \n[00:02:44] CM: He has said many times that if you don’t have a job - if you end up doing nothing, you can fall back on um working at this takeaway. And I say “Errr [...] no thanks. But err [...] thanks, but no thanks”\n\n[00:02:58] INTERVIEWER: [Laughs]. It’s nice to have that safety net. \n', 'Business;Family;Food;', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1hlztRHw1wvgWvZtw_LOVClyg8nxV5cZrnDFpuBtFcIs/edit?usp=sharing', NULL, 'Jess C.', 'Uncertain words - need verification', 0, 0),
(10019, '10011', 'Lisa Lee', NULL, '2020s', 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Economic', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Other', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] INTERVIEWER: Pre-pandemic growing up in the takeaway, did you ever felt people vandalising your shop? Or did you have annoying customers that would leave rice and chips everywhere? That kinda thing,\n\n[00:00:11] LL: Oh my God, I felt that I would get so pissed off. And my dad, my dad is a very gentle person by nature and he- his life philosophy was literally to just keep your head down and to keep the peace because you just don’t know - and I am coming to understand that I don’t agree with that because that means if we were to be attacked then there is a high chance I would [???].\n[00:00:38] LL: So, in terms of growing up, there was one incident where I think it was just tomfoolery more than anything. But I remember it because I think I was just sleeping in my cot effectively until I was maybe three or four. \n[00:00:55] LL: But in the middle of the night, two men climbed in front of our shop and we were sleeping. We were living upstairs and they broke through the window.\n\n[00:01:04] INTERVIEWER: In your bedroom window?\n\n[00:01:06] LL: In our bedroom, so yeah, so I was in [...] I obviously shared a room with my parents. They were in the bed, I was in my cot. And then they were so drunk. They were just mucking around. But obviously it was terrifying to have full-grown drunk men in your room, swinging on your bedroom light and you have no idea what’s going on.\n[00:01:26] LL: So my parents did call the police. I remember the police being there. And actually, talking about the police, I have had several experiences dealing with them and I have to say I understand why the Chinese community is so [???]  don’t call on them for help because they are really not that supportive. \n[00:01:43] LL: So nothing came from that as far as I know and then after we would get customers who would come in and just eat in our takeaway and leave a mess. And my dad would just you know obviously, [???] just clean it up. \n[00:01:56] LL: Nothing violent comes to mind, although, the most recent incident that happened. And this is the thing with hate crime, it’s really hard to say it’s because of racism. Our driver was outside of the takeaway and then a cyclist came and then maybe he accidentally knocked into the car. He got off the bike. He went after the driver. Driver’s obviously freaked out. Ran into the takeaway for safety and my dad and him tried to pole down the doors and the man couldn’t get in because he was furious. \n[00:02:30] LL: And then the man basically smashed the glass on the door. The glass went everywhere and it cut my dad’s face and it misses his eye by centimeters. As soon as he saw my dad bleeding he like ran away. \n[00:02:44] LL: But what if we hadn’t been a Chinese takeaway? We’d tried thinking if it was a different business owned by different marginalised person? Or White person? So, my dad was very good about it, but I wonder at the back of my mind how he actually felt about it, being much older and he’s not in his (you know) youth where he can handle something like that. As well as he could have.\n\n[00:03:10] INTERVIEWER: I’m sorry that happened.\n', 'Business;Crime;Family;Food;Racism', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/16u-liwoOLXnc3pNDBuqzabfs_ebFUy59qqhGypoXWCg/edit?usp=sharing', NULL, 'Jess C.', 'Contains Cantonese', 0, 0),
(10020, '10012', 'Tom Tse', NULL, '2020s', 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Economic', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Other', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] INTERVIEWER: What were your thoughts and feelings at the time when you were kinda growing up and working in the Chinese takeaway? Were you still helping out as well on weekends?\n\n[00:00:08] TT: I do help out every now and then when I go back to York to visit. In terms of how I felt about it, because I was young I was probably ungrateful for it. Because I started helping out in the takeaway since primary school, working on the weekends as well. That’s when all your friends do stuff on the weekend as well.\n[00:00:25] TT: Working from probably like half five to midnight, I probably saw it as “Ahh”, a bit jealous that my friends get to do stuff. I didn’t get to make a lot of friends during secondary school for example.  \n[00:00:36] TT: But at the same time I’m kinda glad I didn’t really do half the stuff that I heard on the weekends. It also gave me like a lot of discipline, gave me a lot of practical skills later on in life as well. For example, I’m quite surprised when I went to uni, I saw a lot of people doesn’t [sic.] know how to cook. Something simple as that. \n[00:00:53] TT: But I’m very grateful for what they’ve done to, like, I was thinking about this the other day how it would be like if we opened a Chinese takeaway now. Can we do it? They sacrificed a lot just to give us comfortable living as well. It’s something we have to be grateful for.\n[00:01:10] TT: Thinking about this the other day as well; I always ask them do they even enjoy what they are doing? And I am really scared of asking that because who actually enjoys takeaway life? [...] It’s a very difficult lifestyle. \n\n[00:01:24] INTERVIEWER: Yeah, takeaway life was all about survival for our parents’ era and you know, they sacrificed a lot for themselves so the second generation like us - that we can go on to do better things that aren’t as backbreaking. And I guess what are your thoughts about that when you know, your parents have like sacrificed so much for you?   \n\n[00:01:44] TT: I would hope that I can provide the same things for if I ever have kids, the same experience - like this level of support. Definitely emotionally and financially.\n', 'Business;Family;Food;', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1hSknqGBD_7eBC6uz12gHwK_9pK-3ROdubmfXMa0NVaE/edit?usp=sharing', NULL, 'Jess C.', 'Uncertain words - need verification', 0, 0),
(10021, '10013', 'Winnie Nip', NULL, '2020s', 'Audio', 'Immigration', 'Economic', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Other', NULL, NULL, '[00:00:01] INTERVIEWER: What were your favourite jobs to do in the takeaway? \n\n[00:00:05] WN: I liked stealing chips. [laughs] In between the customers, I would hang around in the kitchen - steal some chips. I also just liked doing nothing that was to do with the takeaway so like reading the trashy magazines, watching Eastenders. \n[00:00:21] WN: But otherwise, things I did like to do is kinda a weird one so I really liked the prep before the shop opened. So, doing all the fried rice, putting the lids on the fried rice to containers. Only because it was very methodical and everyone had like a routine. So, go in the tub, you would collect it, then you’d press the lids on and it would go in a pile.  \n[00:00:47] WN: I really enjoyed that because it was very. It was- what’s the word?  \n\n[00:00:50] INTERVIEWER: Therapeutic, I would say?\n\n[00:00:51] WN: There! [laughs]\n\n[00:00:54] INTERVIEWER: When did your parents sell the takeaway? And what were some of your feelings when they sold it? \n\n[00:01:00] WN: They sold the takeaway in 2019, so just before Covid. My dad was ready to sell. I think when you work in that industry it’s so hard to find other chefs to train up. And you put so much of your energy training people up only for people to leave.  \n[00:01:15] WN: And then my dad was at the end of them owning the shop outright, manned a lot of the chef stations so he would be head chef and he would do everything else as well. My mum on the other hand, wasn’t quite ready to sell so she found it really difficult because it was her livelihood. \n[00:01:35] WN: You know, she’s very precious over it and still very protective over it.\n', 'Business;Family;Food;', '', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1lyd1ANHf4Q46r9_iiiTPTa1kqE9UVUKaI1smQaQNjOI/edit?usp=sharing', NULL, 'Jess C.', NULL, 0, 0),
(10022, '10014', 'Stelio Stefanou', NULL, NULL, 'Digital Text', 'Immigration', 'Economic', 'Child Migration', NULL, 'Egypt', 'TCOB', NULL, NULL, 'I was born in Egypt to Greek Cypriot parents. There wasn’t enough land to go around for the boys in my father’s family, so he went to Egypt to make a new life for himself and set up a grocery shop. When the Suez Crisis started in 1956, my parents were forced to leave everything behind. We moved to Britain when I was six years old and I arrived not speaking a word of English. My dad found a job as a shop assistant and eventually leased his own grocery and delicatessen shop. Growing up, I worked in my dad’s shop on the weekends to earn my pocket money. On the train on the way home, my dad would quiz me about our turnover for the day, our average profit margin, our gross profit. He taught me the fundamentals of business. When I decided to expand my company, Accord, I borrowed quite a lot of money – enough to blow me out of the water if I’d failed. But my view was that my dad had lost everything when he was in his 40s. He came to a new country and started again from nothing. Even if I didn’t succeed, I could resurrect myself somehow. By the time I sold Accord in 2007, we were one of the largest maintenance companies in the country, responsible for a large section of the motorway network and half of the social housing in Birmingham, amongst other projects. We did things rather differently than many other companies and I’m proud of having built up a sizable company from small beginnings.', 'Africa;Egypt;Commerce;Family;Politics;Work', '', NULL, NULL, 'Kate', NULL, 0, 0),
(10023, '10015', 'Carlton Cummings', NULL, NULL, 'Digital Text', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Barbados', 'TCOB', NULL, NULL, 'I have an annoying habit of questioning things and trying to figure out new ways of doing things. I became interested in lithium-ion batteries, which are used in electric cars and are now even powering buildings and homes. The companies producing these batteries don’t really think about what’s going to happen when they’ve reached the end of their lifespans. The batteries are put together in a way that is difficult to take apart, with lots of glue, lots of welding and other components that can’t be disassembled. What we did was re-imagine how batteries are put together so that they can be easily taken apart and repaired or upgraded, reducing the amount of electronic waste that is produced. The world is going to transition into a lot more renewable energy in the next few years, and we want to play a role in helping the world do it right. Currently we sell our products in the UK, the Caribbean and East Africa. Representation is important. I was born and raised in Barbados, and I have a personal understanding of the problems faced by people living in other parts of the world. It tends to forge strong business relationships in developing markets, because people trust and know that you’ve experienced what they are dealing with.', 'Africa,Barbados;Commerce;North America;Work', '', NULL, NULL, 'Kate', NULL, 0, 0),
(10024, '10016', 'Herman Hauser', NULL, NULL, 'Digital Text', 'Immigration', 'Education', NULL, NULL, 'Austria', 'TCOB', NULL, NULL, 'I was born in Vienna, but I grew up in Tyrol in the Alps, in a village of 200 people. When I was 15 years old, my father decided that I should go to the UK to learn English because, in his opinion, English was the most important language in the world. I came to Cambridge to study at an English language school and returned to do my PhD there before starting my technology career. My father was an entrepreneur; he was in the wine business, conversation around the dinner table revolved around business and I suppose that rubbed off on me. I met Chris Curry after finishing my PhD at Cambridge and he said we ought to start a company. It only cost about £50 to incorporate, and it was one of the great advantages that Britain had at that time. If it had cost £1000, we might not have started the company! Microprocessors were all the rage at the time, a bit like AI now. It was one of those subjects that inspired a generation and we got swept away by the idea that everybody could have a computer with this chip. That was the start of Acorn Computers. In addition to Acorn, I’m proud of creating ARM. On average every smartphone has 15 to 20 ARM microprocessors. Pretty much any electronic device has ARMs. We’ve sold 160 billion ARMs and so, on average, every single person in the world has 20 ARMs. It’s very exciting to have created something that’s now used by the majority of people around the world every day.', 'Austria;Education;EU;Europe;Commerce;Family;Work', '', NULL, NULL, 'Kate', NULL, 0, 0),
(10025, '10017', 'Nabil Al-Kinani', NULL, NULL, 'Digital Text', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Iraq', 'TCOB', NULL, NULL, 'Back home in Iraq, people would invite each other to their homes to socialise. But because we live in smaller spaces and face a variety of issues with respect to housing, it’s difficult to invite friends over in this country. Ahwangy creates a place that fills this gap. A typical shisha order will cost you £15 to £20 – you can smoke shisha at home for much less. But our customers spend their money with us for the experience of socialising with individuals from their home culture. As a first-generation migrant, my yearning for home is reflected in Ahwangy. We’re frequently visited by an Arabic group of traditional singers – they come here every Sunday night, and perform songs that my father used to listen to. I’m not turning a profit when these songs are performed – neither am I turning a profit when we decorate the walls with traditional art and photography. But I do it for people who are looking for that cultural experience, and people who want to learn about and remember their historical origins.', 'Asia;Commerce;Community;Culture;Friends;Iraq;Music', '', NULL, NULL, 'Kate', NULL, 0, 0),
(10026, '10018', 'Althea McNish', NULL, NULL, 'Digital Text', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Trinidad and Tobago', 'TCOB', NULL, NULL, '“Whenever printers told me it couldn’t be done, I would show them how to do it. Before long, the impossible became possible.” – Althea McNish in Women Design by Libby Sellers, 2018. Soon after the Second World War, 27-year-old Althea McNish moved from Trinidad to the gloomy, grey world of London, bringing with her a ‘tropical eye’ that would transform British textiles and fashion. Althea studied at the Central School of Art and Design and the Royal College of Art, where she produced designs inspired by the British landscape, but with a feel of the Caribbean. On seeing her graduation show, the chairman of Liberty’s, the department store, commissioned her to create a range of fabrics. Her bold, colourful patterns set Althea’s work apart from what was commonly available at the time, and she was commissioned by many of the leading textile manufacturers of the day. Among these was Zika Ascher, a Czech immigrant textile manufacturer, who supplied her silk-printed fabrics to couture clients, including Christian Dior. Althea also taught throughout her career and was an active member of the Caribbean Arts Movement, which was founded to celebrate the work of artists, writers, filmmakers and musicians from across the Caribbean and to promote them to the British public.', 'Education;Commerce;Culture;North America;Trinidad and Tobago;Work', '', NULL, NULL, 'Kate', NULL, 0, 0),
(10027, '10019', 'Antonio Nigro', NULL, NULL, 'Digital Text', 'Immigration', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Italy', 'TCOB', NULL, NULL, 'When I arrived in London aged 19, I was shocked because I come from a village of just 4,500 people in Puglia, in the heel of Italy. I took a job washing dishes at an Italian restaurant in north London and worked my way up to sous-chef. It was very hard, but after five years I was able to put some money aside which I used to buy this place from an Italian family that had run it since the early 1980s. You can imagine after 20 years I’ve heard so many stories – so many lives, so many problems, so many sad things but so many beautiful things also. Sometimes you get very close to your customers – it’s like they become a part of your existence. When we close at night and I see my staff, even if they are tired, they are happy because they’ve had a good day with me, my customers are happy and when I get home, my kids are happy to see me. There is nothing better than when what you do is appreciated. It’s the biggest motivation you could have.', 'EU;Europe;Commerce;Food;Italy;Work', '', NULL, NULL, 'Kate', NULL, 0, 0),
(10028, '10020', 'Awon Golding', NULL, NULL, 'Digital Text', 'Immigration', 'Education', NULL, NULL, 'Hong Kong;India', 'TCOB', NULL, NULL, 'Not being part of the ingrained culture here means that I have a fresh perspective on things. I really cherish my different-ness. My mother is from the Tangkhul Naga tribe in Northeast India, and Dad is from Essex, but I was born and raised in Hong Kong. I’m a third-culture kid. I’d always been an avid hat wearer and lover. Thirteen years ago, I decided to come to London to study millinery. It’s been a very rocky road, but I’m lucky to have my own studio and my own brand. And for the last three years, I’ve also been working as the head millinery designer for Lock & Co, which is the world’s oldest hat shop. It’s a 400-year-old heritage brand that is synonymous with Britishness, and I’m at the helm of the design, which is pretty incredible. I always want to create something in my work that brings a little bit of joy into your life. My favourite pieces are my gelato hats. These were from my first collection but I’m still incredibly proud of them.', 'Asia;Commerce;Culture;Education;Hong Kong;India;Pride;Work', '', NULL, NULL, 'Kate', NULL, 0, 0);
